<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Counting of Votes Slow in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, May 13 (Xinhua) -- The counting of votes for the
Philippine national and local elections had been slow due to the
introduction of a new electoral system in Monday's polls and the
handling of complaints about cheating, a private watchdog
organization said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The watchdog, the National Citizens' Movement for Free
Elections (Namfrel), is the sole non-governmental organization
authorized by the Commission on Elections to conduct a quick count
of the votes.
</P>
<P>
Namfrel Secretary General Guillermo Luz said at a press
conference that the organization had decided to temporarily shelve
the tabulation for the party list system.
</P>
<P>
The party list system was introduced in Monday's elections to
enable small political parties and marginalized and
under-represented sectors to obtain possible representation in the
House of Representatives, which was traditionally dominated by big
political parties.
</P>
<P>
In the polls, 52 members of the House of Representatives were
being chosen under the party list system while the rest by
district.
</P>
<P>
Luz explained that Namfrel was not dropping the party list
system, but just setting it aside because it caused confusion and
delay in the counting of the ballots at the precinct level where
some voters voted for the sector without indicating the party's
name while others only wrote the abbreviation of the party.
</P>
<P>
"In areas where there was slowing-down in count we anticipate
it could be caused by the party list," he said. "But we are not
dropping the party list."
</P>
<P>
Another reason for the delay in counting was that some ruling
party candidates filed petitions claiming there was cheating in
the elections. They asked the Commission on Elections to stop
counting the ballots at some precincts.
</P>
<P>
Namfrel, warning that a halt to the counting would affect the
tabulation at the national level, urged the Commission on
Elections to immediately handle the petitions.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Luz said, the failure of some election inspectors to
give a copy of the election returns to Namfrel volunteers also
contributed to the delay.
</P>
<P>
Namfrel had counted votes cast at only 9.26 percent of the
174,000 precincts across the country. It said it would release the
final result within 10 days after the voting day.
</P>
<P>
The counting conducted by employees and workers of the
Commission on Elections was also slow. As of Wednesday, the poll
body had not yet released any official figures.
</P>
<P>
After the counting of votes at the precinct level, the election
returns would be transferred to the municipal or city level where
the total votes of the returns will be recorded and tabulated on
the certificate of canvass.
</P>
<P>
Then the certificate would be sent to the provincial level
which would then give the forms to the House of Representatives
for the counting of presidential and vice presidential positions
while the Commission on Elections will count the votes for the
senatorial and party list positions.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, the official result of the elections would not be
known for about four weeks.
</P>
<P>
Outgoing President Fidel Ramos has already expressed disgust
over the slowness of the canvassing of votes three days after the
elections ended.
</P>
<P>
About 80 percent of the 34 million registered voters went to
the polls on Monday to elect a new president, a new vice
president, 12 out of 24 senators, all the 260 members of the House
of Representatives and more than 17,000 local officials and
councilors.
</P>
<P>
According to the latest unofficial figures released by Namfrel,
Vice President Joseph Estrada of the opposition Laban ng
Makabayang Masang Pilipino (Fight of Patriotic Filipino Masses)
continued to take a commanding lead with 884,106 votes.
</P>
<P>
House Speaker Jose de Venecia, Ramos' anointed candidate of the
ruling Lakas-NUCD party, was ranked third with 320,008 votes.
</P>
<P>
In the vice presidential race, senator Gloria Macapagal Arroyo
of the ruling party further consolidated her lead with 932,933
votes, far ahead of the other eight candidates.
</P>
<P>
However, Ramos said it was too early to say Estrada had won the
presidency as only a small portion of the votes had been counted.
</P>
<P>
"I think it is a little premature to be looking sad as you are
speculating about some happenings which may be clarified in the
next three of four days," he said.
</P>
<P>
"What have not been reported are the bailiwicks (overwhelming
victory) of the Lakas. For instance, Pangasinan is not yet in, "
he said, indicating that De Venecia had won overwhelmingly in his
home province. 
</P>
</TEXT>
