<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Examines National Employment Plans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, May 13 (Xinhua) -- The European employment
commissioner Wednesday described as real progress the national job
creation action plans (NAPs) by individual European Union member
states.
</P>
<P>
Padraig Flynn made the remark after the European Commission
completed its examination of the NAPs.
</P>
<P>
"The fact that all 15 member states, in spite of the very tight
time frame of only four months, have prepared, adopted and
delivered their NAPs by the end of April 1998, constitutes in
itself a major political achievement," the commissioner told a
European Parliament hearing at Strasbourg.
</P>
<P>
The NAPs set out measures for implementing the 1998 employment
guidelines adopted last December by the European council, at
heads of state and government level in Luxembourg.
</P>
<P>
Flynn rated all the NAPs as very serious and well-done, but set
aside Spain's and France's as highly presentable and with
transparency.
</P>
<P>
The commission, the executive body of the 15-nation European
Union, examined what the member states have committed themselves
to doing, and assessed whether they are in line with the
objectives of the 1998 employment guidelines.
</P>
<P>
The commission's assessment of the NAPs will serve as the basis
for a discussion scheduled for the next European summit at
Cardiff, Britain. 
</P>
</TEXT>
