<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-13 14:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jerusalem Mayor Pledges to Stem Anti-Arab Violence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, May 13 (Xinhua) - Jerusalem Mayor Ehud Olmert on
Wednesday promised to take measures to stop the surging anti-Arab
violence in the city.
</P>
<P>
Olmert made the promise following a stabbing incident Wednesday
morning in the city's Ultra-Orthodox neighborhood of Mea Shearim,
in which an Arab man was stabbed to death by a suspected Jewish
extremist, Israel Radio reported.
</P>
<P>
The Wednesday stabbing was the sixth attack on Arabs in the
same area over the past six months, though it was the first fatal
one.
</P>
<P>
The victim, reportedly a Bedouin Arab man in his 50s, was
walking through Mea Shearim at dawn, apparently on his way to
work, when he was stabbed several times, police said.
</P>
<P>
Police sealed off the area and detained one man, who was later
freed due to want of proof.
</P>
<P>
Police believed that an assailant, who obviously avenged
attacks by Arabs on Jews, was responsible for all six attacks.
</P>
<P>
Olmert said he viewed with "grave concern" the violence against
the Arabs and vowed to take measures to protect the Arab residents
just as he did for the Jewish ones.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Communist Hadash Party said the Wednesday attack was
"further proof of the deeply planted anti-Arab sentiment" among
Jews.
</P>
<P>
It strongly criticized Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu for fostering the atmosphere that led to the violence
by failing to condemn such attacks.
</P>
<P>
There has been a surge of terrorist attacks by both Jewish and
Arab extremists in Jerusalem at a time when the
Israeli-Palestinian peace talks are deeply stranded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
