<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai To Reinforce Taiwan Investors Protection Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, May 13 (Xinhua) -- Starting today, the Standing
Committee of the Shanghai Municipal People's Congress began to
examine the enforcement of the Law on the Protection of
Investments of Taiwan Compatriots.
</P>
<P>
This was to further improve Shanghai's soft environment for
attracting overseas funds and push the development of both
Shanghai and Taiwan, according to Chen Tiedi, Chairman of the
Standing Committee of the Shanghai Municipal People's Congress.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai is the largest industrial city in China. Up to March,
the city had approved more than 3,100 Taiwan-funded projects with
more than 3.4 billion U.S. dollars worth of signed contracts,
accounting for 11.4 percent of the total overseas funds in the
city.
</P>
<P>
According to Chen, since the Law on the Protection of
Investments of Taiwan Compatriots was issued four years ago by the
National People's Congress, Shanghai has formulated a series of
corresponding codes and regulations to better enforce the law.
</P>
<P>
She said the examination will last half a month and investors
from Taiwan are welcome to make complaints and offer suggestions.
</P>
</TEXT>
