<HEADLINE> India Claims it Can Withstand Sanctions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, May 13 (Xinhua) -- India, defying strong criticism
worldwide over its nuclear tests, says it "will be able to bear"
any possible international sanctions.
</P>
<P>
Indian Vice-President Krishna Kant told a press conference
Wednesday, at the end of the Group-15 summit here, that India, "as
a united country", carried out the tests after "a great deal of
deliberation."
</P>
<P>
India set off three nuclear devices on Monday and also tested a
short-range Trident missile, capable of hitting targets up to 350
kilometers away.
</P>
<P>
The tests, the first since 1974, have sparked worldwide
concerns and strong protests in the international community with
some countries threatening economic sanctions.
</P>
<P>
Japan, India's largest aid donor since 1986, decided to suspend
new grants-in-aid to the South Asia nation, and the United States
is considering economic sanctions.
</P>
<P>
Kant said: "India has not violated any international treaty or
agreement signed by us up to now." He said: "India remains
committed to the process of nuclear disarmament, leading to total
global disarmament."
</P>
<P>
He reiterated that his country would be prepared to consider
adhering to some of the undertakings in the comprehensive test ban
treaty. But obviously, this could not be done in a vacuum...and
would depend on a number of reciprocal activities." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
