<HEADLINE> China Introduces Semis in National Swimming Meet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAODING, Northeast China, May 13 (Xinhua) -- China will for the
first time introduce the semi-finals in its national swimming
championships here on Friday in accordance with the decision made
by the world swimming governing body FINA.
</P>
<P>
More than 410 swimmers from 29 clubs will take part in the
one-week national swimming meet.
</P>
<P>
World record holder Chen Yan, winner of the women's 400-meter
individual medley and 400m freestyle, and Wu Yanyan, world
champion of the 200m individual medley at the world swimming
championships in Perth, will spearhead their compatriots to
compete in the newly-formatted competition with semifinals.
</P>
<P>
However, women's freestyle sprint queen Le Jingyi, world record
holder of both 50m and 100m, will be absent from the pool.
</P>
<P>
"She is now concentrating on her schooling at a university in
Shanghai," a coach from Shanghai said.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese Swimming Association will open an anti-doping
conference here on Thursday to discuss measures to toughen doping
control in the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
