<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Stock Market Develops Despite Asian Financial Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 13 (Xinhua) -- China's stock market has been
affected little by the Asian financial crisis and is continuing
its steady growth momentum, a senior securities industry official
said here today.
</P>
<P>
"The Chinese stock market has been growing stably since the
start of this year, with the major indices on a steady rise both
in Shanghai and Shenzhen," said Chen Yaoxian, vice-chairman of the
China Securities Regulatory Commission, at an investment forum
sponsored by Credit Lyonnais Securities Asia.
</P>
<P>
He also said that the amount of funds raised by Chinese
companies through share issues soared more than 30 percent in the
first four months of this year compared with the same period last
year. He did not give the specific figure.
</P>
<P>
Chen attributed the steady development of the Chinese stock
market amid the Asian financial crisis mainly to the country's
successful economic "soft landing" and stern market supervision.
</P>
<P>
Official figures show that China's stock market has developed
rapidly since it was founded more than seven years ago. By early
this week more than 800 Chinese companies had been listed at home
stock exchanges in Shanghai and Shenzhen as well as Hong Kong, New
York and Singapore.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Chinese investors have opened more than 34 million
stock trading accounts.
</P>
<P>
Chen said at today's forum that China's stock market
capitalization had exceeded two trillion yuan (240 million
U.S. dollars) by the end April, up 18.7 percent since the end of
last year.
</P>
<P>
As more companies get listed and more investors buy stocks, the
stock market is gaining a role in China's national economy,
observers here said.
</P>
<P>
Statistics indicate that the securities market has raised more
than 250 billion yuan for the nation's enterprises. The funds have
not only helped to ease the financial difficulties of state-owned
enterprises but also boosted their corporate transformation.
</P>
<P>
As time passes, Chinese stock investors have also grown more
rational, basing their trading decisions increasingly on
macro-economic performance and company efficiency.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980513.0030 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Internet Ad' Revenue Rises in Canada </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, May 13 (Xinhua) -- Revenues from Canadian firms selling
advertizing space on the Internet reached almost 10 million
Canadian dollars (seven million U.S. dollars) last year.
</P>
<P>
A year earlier, online ad revenue in Canada was only 1.6
million dollars, according to figures from the Internet
Advertising Bureau of Canada, an organization of marketing
professionals formed at the end of last year.
</P>
<P>
The bureau predicted revenue could more than double to 22.9
million dollars this year and 56.9 million in 1999.
</P>
<P>
It found that financial services led the way, generating 2.1
million dollars in ad's revenue. That is in line with growth in
areas such as PC banking and electronic commerce.
</P>
<P>
Ted Boyd, vice chairman of the bureau, said the research
results will help identify emerging trends and growth areas in the
industry that were not measurable before. 
</P>
</TEXT>
