<DOCNO> XIE19980513.0034 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Discussion over Cattle Shipment to DPRK Under Way </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, May 13 (Xinhua) -- Inter-Korea discussion over the
delivery of 1,000 South Korean cattle to the Democratic People's
Republic of Korea (DPRK) is well underway, a South Korean
government source said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The negotiations came after the South Korean business tycoon,
Chung Ju-yung, founder and honorary chairman of Hyundai Business
Group, last week promised a donation of 1,000 oxes to the DPRK
through the truce village of Panmunjom.
</P>
<P>
The plan to donate cattle is unprecedented in South Korea's
food aid program for the DPRK.
</P>
<P>
The discussion focuses on how to prevent foot-and-mouth
disease, which is reportedly prevalent in the DPRK, from spreading
to South Korea after cattle delivery over land.
</P>
<P>
Kim Young-jin, representative of the ruling National Congress
for New Politics, warned parliament Tuesday that
cattle-transporting trucks returning from the North could bring
back the disease.
</P>
<P>
Foot-and-mouth disease is a contagious, viral disease of cattle
and other hoofed animals, characterized by blisters in the mouth
and about the hoofs.
</P>
<P>
The sterilization of trucks returning from the North would be
nearly impossible, he said.
</P>
<P>
"If the disease spreads to our country, our livestock industry
will be hit hard and we won't be able to export hoofed animals,''
he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980513.0035 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India's Actions Not to Go Unanswered: Pakistan FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, May 13 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Foreign Minister Gohar
Ayub Khan said Wednesday that India's nuclear tests "pose an
immediate and grave threat to Pakistan's security and will not go
unanswered."
</P>
<P>
The news India conducted two more nuclear tests Wednesday
provides further confirmation "about India's consistent pattern of
irresponsible behavior," Gohar said in a statement to the Senate.
</P>
<P>
"The blind pursuit of intrinsic and inherent hegemonic
impulses, reflected so often in Indian behavior and ignored
largely by the international community, despite Pakistan's
repeated efforts to draw attention to them, has definitely
encouraged and emboldened India to throw all caution to the
winds," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that the invoking of mandatory sanctions under the U.S.
Laws against India "hardly constitutes an effective response to
Indian provocative actions or compensates for errors of judgment,
which have seriously disrupted the regional strategic balance."
</P>
<P>
"Pakistan once again reiterates that responsibility for
consequences that will inevitably ensue would lie squarely with
India and those who have colluded and acquiesced in the
weaponization of India's nuclear program," he said. 
</P>
