<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada, US Moving Towards a Wheat War </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, May 13 (Xinhua) -- Canada and the United States could
be moving towards another wheat war if the U.S. again subsidizes
its grain exports.
</P>
<P>
In an unusual move, three Canadian ministers warned the U.S.
Tuesday that there could be a huge fallout from plans by the
United States to bring back its export enhancement program,
according to the Financial Post newspaper.
</P>
<P>
Ralph Goodale, minister responsible for the Canadian Wheat
Board, said if the U.S. used the program to subsidize exports,
U.S. domestic grain prices would soar artificially.
</P>
<P>
"That will undoubtedly create greater commercial pressure for
Canadian grain to flow south," he was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
It's "not because of anything Canada has done, but as a direct
consequences of a market distortion created by the United States,"
he noted.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. administration said this week it is reviving the
program to target specific farm exports that are being shut out
of foreign markets.
</P>
<P>
Any step by the U.S. to reintroduce the program with wheat
"would have a negative impact on our countries' shared goal of
moving towards the complete elimination of trade subsidies,"
Canadian Trade Minister Sergio Marchi warned.
</P>
<P>
It was the U.S. administration's use of the export enhancement
program in 1994 that led to a brief wheat war between the two
countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
