<DOCNO> XIE19980513.0037 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Monetary Policy Adopted by Central Bank to Stimulate Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 13 (Xinhua) -- The People's Bank of China (PBOC),
the central bank, has implemented a series of monetary and credit
measures to stimulate the domestic market and encourage commercial
banks to enhance money and credit supply.
</P>
<P>
The central bank hopes the package will help China attain its
goal of achieving a Gross Domestic Product (GDP) growth rate of 8
percent while holding inflation to 3 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
Before the Chinese Lunar New Year holiday in late January, the
central bank added 78 billion yuan in discount loans to wholly
state-owned commercial banks to help them deal with the peak for
spending during the holiday.
</P>
<P>
On Jan. 1, the PBOC relaxed controls on the limit for
commercial bank loans, and issued a credit-guiding plan for
state-owned banks in 1998, achieving the transition from direct
control to indirect adjustment of the total amount of money and
credit.
</P>
<P>
On March 21, the PBOC reformed its system of reserve funds for
deposits by restoring the fund's payment and clearance function.
</P>
<P>
On the same day, it lowered interest rates for reserve funds
for deposits and for discounts loans.
</P>
<P>
Four days later, the PBOC lowered the interest rates for
deposits by an average of 0.16 percent and those for loans by an
average of 0.6 percent. The falling rates resulted in a reduction
of more than 30 billion yuan in interest payments for enterprises,
which came as a great relief for China's debt-ridden state-owned
industries.
</P>
<P>
The central bank has also enhanced analysis and monitoring of
the economic and financial situations to increase its guidance on
the commercial banks, declaring that it will grant discount loans
to commercial banks only if there are fund shortages for
commercial loans.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
