worldwide, and also senior Chinese officials and entrepreneurs
from the state sector.
</P>
<P>
"China has risen into one of the hottest investment
destinations in the world, and the forum is aimed at bridging the
gap between the international investors and Chinese enterprises by
enhancing the investors' understanding of the nation," said Gary
Coull, chairman and chief executive officer with Credit Lyonnais
Securities Ltd. (CLSA), sponsor of the forum.
</P>
<P>
The participating fund managers handle more than four trillion
U.S. dollars in financial assets, almost four times the Gross
Domestic Product of China, said Coull, adding that these managers
make investments globally but have a particular interest in China
and want to commit more funds to the nation.
</P>
<P>
This morning, the forum also heard keynote presentations from
senior Chinese officials such as Chen Yuan, president of the State
Development Bank and Chen Yaoxian, vice-chairman of the China
Securities Regulatory Commission.
</P>
<P>
The forum will last three days.
</P>
<P>
With its total assets valued at more than 280 billion U.S.
dollars, the Lyonnais Group is one of the biggest banks in
Europe. The CLSA under the group is mainly involved in the
investment banking business in Asia and is rated as one of the top
research companies in the world. 
