<HEADLINE> Rumor of Police-Peddler Conflict Denied </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, May 13 (Xinhua) -- A spokesman with the city
government of Chengdu, capital of southwest China's Sichuan
Province, today denied a widely spread rumor of police-peddler
conflict.
</P>
<P>
A recent rumor said that late last month 3,000 street peddlers
clashed with 800 local police and that some people were injured or
killed.
</P>
<P>
The rumor was cited as first being announced by a New
York-based human rights organization through the Internet.
</P>
<P>
According to the spokesman, "there was no conflict at all,
and not any deaths or injuries."
</P>
<P>
He said the police were just doing their job persuading some
peddlers to move into a new shopping building in accordance with
the city planning program, and most of the street peddlers showed
their understanding for the city government's decision.
</P>
<P>
He explained that the reason for moving the peddlers to a new
building was that the original area was being demolished and
rebuilt.
</P>
<P>
"So far, all the street peddlers have moved into the new
building and the demolition and rebuilding work has been started,"
he said. 
