<HEADLINE> SKorean President Warns Against Violent Demonstration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, May 13 (Xinhua) -- South Korean President Kim Dae-jung
on Wednesday urged labor unions which are preparing for mass
rallies this weekend to cancel these plans, or to act unharmfully.
</P>
<P>
The president warned that foreign investors will never return
if the rallies become violent again.
</P>
<P>
Kim directed the authorities to prohibit radical students from
joining forces with the labor workers, and to prevent the rally
people from using firebombs and steel pipes.
</P>
<P>
The government will guarantee workers freedom to assemble but
will not tolerate violent demonstrations, as was the case in the
May Day protests, he said.
</P>
<P>
Radical students joined the May Day celebrations organized by
the Korean Confederation of Trade Unions on May 1.
</P>
<P>
The celebrations turned into violent street protests, in which
riot police fired tear gas at protesters who wielded steel pipes
and threw rocks and firebombs.
</P>
<P>
The president blamed the demonstrators for damaging efforts by
the government to improve the economic crisis-plagued nation's
international confidence and ability to attract foreign investment.
</P>
<P>
The president appealed to workers to accept layoffs to help
firms sharpen competitiveness, help restructure corporations and
create jobs in the long run.
</P>
<P>
South Korea cannot draw foreign investment without ensuring
flexibility in the local labor market, he added.
</P>
<P>
The recent labor demonstations have put Kim's government on
shaky ground as it fears that a recurrence of violent
demonstrations will badly influence his struggles to overcome the
economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
South Korea, once the world's dynamic economy, plunged into
economic turmoil in late 1997, and needed a foreign money inflow
to make way out of the situation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
