<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Growth of Rural Industry Vital to China's Economy (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 13 (Xinhua) -- The growth of rural industry has
never so closely linked with the growth of China's national
economy today.
</P>
<P>
The speed of its development has a weighty bearing on whether
or not China can achieve its annual economic target of an
eight-percent growth for this year.
</P>
<P>
The predicted growth of 18 percent for rural industrial
enterprises this year mean much to an eight-percent growth for
China's national economy in the wake of the Asian financial crisis
and inefficient performance of the state sector.
</P>
<P>
In a recent inspection to east China's Jiangsu Province, the
cradle of rural industrial development, Jiang Zemin, general
secretary of the Communist Party of China (CPC) Central Committee,
said that the development of rural industry is of strategic
importance to the national economy.
</P>
<P>
"Whenever the added-value of township-run enterprises grow
three or four percent, the gross domestic product will increase by
one percent," said a noted Chinese economist.
</P>
<P>
To ensure an eight-percent national economic growth,
township-run enterprises should keep a growth rate of no less than
18 percent, or a net increase of 324 billion yuan this year, thus
contributing 3.6 percent to the GDP, he said.
</P>
<P>
A high economic growth rate for rural industry will also
accelerate agricultural development, increase the annual income of
farmers and create more job opportunities, said Chen Jianbo, a
deputy research fellow at the Development Research Center under
the State Council.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980513.0047 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Growth of Rural Industry Vital to China's Economy (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
As a major invention of hundreds of millions of farmers and a
brilliant achievement of China's economic reforms, township-run
enterprises have succeeded in raising the ratio of its added-value
in the GDP from four percent to 33 percent in less than two
decades, becoming a pillar of the country's economy.
</P>
<P>
Thus far, the added-value of township-run enterprises across
China has risen to 1.8 trillion yuan, accounting for two thirds of
the total rural added-value, half of the national industrial
added-value and 38 percent of China's export value.
</P>
<P>
Referring to whether or not the 24 million strong rural
enterprises can maintain its rising momentum, Chen Yaobang,
minister of agriculture, said it should and can attain its goal of
an 18-percent growth.
</P>
<P>
He cited a number of favorable elements including a relatively
strong strength of rural enterprises, government policies
favorable to the development of this sector, abundant farm
produce and labor force and increased government investment in
infrastructures and high-tech firms.
</P>
<P>
More than 6,400 large-and medium-sized rural enterprises are
now quite competitive on the international and domestic
market. Among them, 1,000 firms have obtained the rights of
exporting their own products independently, 4,000 have opened
branches abroad and 40 firms have been listed on the stock market.
</P>
<P>
Jiang Yongtao, director of the Township-run Enterprise Bureau
under the Ministry of Agriculture, said, rural enterprises will
keep developing so long as the state support them in terms of
credit, export, use of investment and technological upgrading.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
