<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Boeing 737 Inspection Has No Effect on China Aviation: Officials </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 13 (Xinhua) -- Orders on safety inspection of
Boeing 737 aircraft recently announced by the Federal Aviation
Administration (FAA) of the United States will not affect the
safety situation in China, civil aviation said here today.
</P>
<P>
Both officials from the Civil Aviation Administration of China
(CAAC) and the China Company of Boeing Commercial Airplane Group
expressed that opinion in an interview with Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
The FAA demanded on Sunday that U.S. air carriers conduct
inspections within seven days, on Boeing 737 aircraft series 100
through 500 that have flown more than 50,000 hours, and within 14
days on those aircraft that have flown more than 40,000 hours. The
inspections will focus on the electrical wiring and conduit inside
fuel tanks.
</P>
<P>
On April 25, an FAA official found two small holes caused by a
short circuit on wiring "sleeves" near an oil tank on the wings of
a Boeing 737 belonging to U.S. carrier Continental Airlines.
</P>
<P>
Inspectors expressed doubts that the explosion of a Boeing 747
near New York City in 1996 should be blamed on a short-circuit
fire near its fuel tank.
</P>
<P>
China's air carriers now have 141 Boeing 737 airliners of
different types, accounting for nearly one-third of its combined
air fleet, with Boeing 737-300 aircraft the largest component.
</P>
<P>
China began to introduce Boeing aircraft in the mid-1980s, and
the oldest has flown only 32,000 hours. Only 17 Boeing 737
airliners have flown more than 20,000 hours. All of them do not
fall within the range of inspection.
</P>
<P>
"The public need not to worry about the safety of travel by
Chinese airlines," said Zhang Yongsheng, deputy director of Air
Worthiness Department of the CAAC.
</P>
<P>
The country reports a sound safety record for airline travel,
with a set of strict, scientific management systems that have
reached advanced world standards in terms of daily care and
high-level maintenance on aircraft.
</P>
<P>
"Safety is the top priority for civil aviation," Zhang
said. "The CAAC still hopes air carriers place great importance on
this. Over the latest routine care time, air carriers should look
over the oil tankers on its Boeing aircraft."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
