<HEADLINE> Malaysia Increases Funds for Small Traders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, May 13 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia announced on
Wednesday a 150 million ringgit (39 million U.S. dollars)
allocation for the Petty Traders Economic Fund (Tekun) and an
additional 50 million ringgit (13 million dollars) for the Small
Entrepreneurs Fund (TUK).
</P>
<P>
With the funds, small entrepreneurs and petty traders in the
country will have 340 million ringgit (90 million U.S. dollars) to
utilize as capital for their ventures, Deputy Prime Minister Anwar
Ibrahim told reporters after a meeting with small entrepreneurs
and petty traders at the Treasury here.
</P>
<P>
Anwar said the additional funds were allocated from the
existing budget and newly-acquired loans from the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
He said details of the allocation for Tekun undertaken as a
pilot project by Universiti Sains Malaysia's Center For Policy
Research would be announced soon.
</P>
<P>
Anwar said loans under TUK would be at an interest rate of 6
percent and repayments could be made fortnightly instead of weekly
previously.
</P>
<P>
He said such assistance would be extended only to small
entrepreneurs and petty traders with a valid license.
</P>
<P>
"We are seeking the cooperation of the (concerned) association
to take action against payment defaulters and we are prepared to
revoke licenses and take legal action if necessary," he said.
</P>
<P>
The small entrepreneurs and petty traders could also obtain
loans from the Amanah Ikhtiar Malaysia (AIM) funds which totaled
100 million ringgit (26 million dollars) announced earlier.
</P>
</TEXT>
