<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Death Toll in Israeli Air Raids Reaches Eight </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, May 13 (Xinhua) -- The death toll of Palestinians
killed by Israeli air raids on eastern Lebanon province of Bekaa
has reached eight, Lebanon's Voice of the People radio reported
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the number of wounded has increased to 40 from the
previous 22.
</P>
<P>
Israeli warplanes fired at least four rockets in three separate
raids from 1:20 a.m. local time (2200 GMT) on the area of Diera
Taniye, central part of Bekaa, less than 10 kilometers from Syrian
border, the radio said.
</P>
<P>
A hospital source said that the wounded Palestinians are now
receiving treatment at nearby hospitals.
</P>
<P>
Israeli raids targeted a training facility possessed by the
Damascus-based Palestinian Fatah Movement led by Colonel Abu
Mousa, and an administrative house owned by the Popular Front for
the Liberation of Palestinian-General Command (PFLP-GC) led by
Ahmmed Giblil.
</P>
<P>
They all had quit Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat's Fatah and
opposed the Palestinian-Israeli peace deal.
</P>
<P>
PFLP-GC in a statement vowed that they will make the Zionist
enemy pay for their savage aggression.
</P>
<P>
In Jerusalem, an Israeli army statement confirmed the raids,
saying Israeli Air Force warplanes Tuesday night attacked
terrorist positions in the area of the Lebanese Bekaa.
</P>
<P>
The pilots reportedly hit the targets and returned safely to
their bases, it added.
</P>
<P>
This was the first Israeli attack on the Palestinian groups in
Lebanon since they fired rockets onto northern Israeli territory
in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli blast came one day after two Israeli soldiers were
wounded by rockets fired by the Muslim resistance group Hezbollah,
or Party of God, which is backed by Iranians.
</P>
<P>
Hezbollah fired several Katyusha missiles onto northern
Israeli area of Galilee Monday night to revenge Lebanese
civilians wounded in earlier Israeli artillery shellings.
</P>
<P>
Since Israel occupied a 1,200-square-kilometer border strip in
south Lebanon in 1985 to buffer guerrilla attacks, Lebanon's
resistance forces have locked Israeli troops and its allied South
Lebanon Army in a war of attrition. 
</P>
</TEXT>
