<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Issue More Investment Funds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 13 (Xinhua) -- China will issue more securities
investment funds this year to develop institutional investors and
ensure market stability, a senior securities industry official
said today.
</P>
<P>
"We will take into consideration the market performance and
unveil new investment funds in the second half of this year," said
Chen Yaoxian, vice chairman of the China Securities Regulatory
Commission, at a forum sponsored by Credit Lyonnais Securities
Asia.
</P>
<P>
China issued its first two securities investment funds, Fund
Jintai and Fund Kaiyuan, in March. The third fund, Xinghua, was
issued in April.
</P>
<P>
The three funds, all closed-end and valued at 2 billion yuan
each, met with great investor enthusiasm immediately after they
were listed on stock exchanges in Shanghai and Shenzhen on April 7
and May 8. They are believed to have triggered the recent
stock-market rebound.
</P>
<P>
Chen revealed that the investment funds to be issued will get
larger in size and China will experiment with open-ended
investment funds when the time is ripe.
</P>
<P>
China will develop different types of securities investment
funds to co-ordinate with each other, Chen told the forum.
</P>
<P>
China is accelerating the formation of its long-awaited
Securities Law and seeking to increase investment instruments, he
added.
</P>
<P>
He affirmed that China will continue to take measures to
develop the B-share market, which is currently in the doldrums,
and said that he personally is confident about prospects of the
market.
</P>
<P>
B shares refer to those issued by Chinese companies but open
for overseas investors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
