<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Baidoa Meeting in Somalia Might Be Postponed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, May 13 (Xinhua) -- There are increasing
speculations, controversial images and hopes in Somalia for the
convening of the Baidoa conference which is scheduled to start
two days from now.
</P>
<P>
According to Abdi Osman Farah, deputy chairman of the Hawadle
political faction (USC/PM), it is not likely that the Cairo
agreement will become productive due to reasons he did not
disclose.
</P>
<P>
Farah, together with five other USC splinter political groups
from the central region of Hiran who held a four-day meeting in
Mogadishu, concluded Tuesday that they won't participate in any
national meeting which is not inclusive for all of Somalia's
multiple factions as they put it.
</P>
<P>
They said, instead, they're now trying to establish an
administration of their own for Hiran region.
</P>
<P>
Abdulkadir Mohamed Aden Zoppe, a prominent leader of the
Rahanwein community of Bay and Bakol regions, said aside from the
financial difficulties, the conference won't start as long as
Hussein Aidid's militiamen remain in the two regions.
</P>
<P>
Zoppe said Hussein Aidid has agreed with the Rahanweins to
pull out from Baidoa in a systematic way and would complete the
withdrawal ten days earlier before the convening of the
conference, but he has not honored his words so far.
</P>
<P>
Hussein Aidid's faction is on the contrary very hopeful that
the Baidoa meeting will bring about a lasting solution for
Somalia's long standing political crises.
</P>
<P>
Mohamed Qanyare Afrah, Hussein Aidid's outspoken interior
secretary, said Wednesday that the logic reaches them that the
Baidoa conference should be postponed for another term, but he
did not indicate when.
</P>
<P>
Afrah said Mogadishu's administration, air and seaports which
are in reach should first be settled as a proof to the world that
something could be done.
</P>
<P>
Faction leader Ali Mahdi Mohamed told Xinhua Wednesday that
Somalia's only hope is in the implementation of the Cairo peace
deal and the Baidoa conference.
</P>
<P>
According to the plan, he said, the Baidoa conference will
follow the establishment of Mogadishu's administration which will
be concluded in the next two days.
</P>
<P>
On the possibility of the postponement of the Baidoa meeting,
Ali Mahdi said it is obvious that it will be postponed, but none
can so far say the final word for its postponement.
</P>
<P>
"The new date will be announced in our next meeting tomorrow
or on Friday," he added.
</P>
<P>
The main backer of the Cairo peace deal, Egypt, is also
optimistic about the convening of the Baidoa meeting for the
formation of a government of national unity for Somalia. Mohamud
Mustafa, Egyptian ambassador to Somalia who is now in Mogadishu,
told Xinhua that it is too early to announce that the Cairo
initiative has failed as far as the Somalis are committed.
</P>
<P>
Mustafa said the Somali faction leaders are now busy in
concluding the administration for Mogadishu, the opening of the
air and seaports, then they will proceed to Baidoa.
</P>
<P>
"It is premature to give a final judgement," he said.
</P>
<P>
Referring to financial support, Mustafa reiterated the full
support of Egypt and the Arab League which are, according to him,
ready to release all the necessary funds for convening the Baidoa
meeting once Mogadishu is settled.
</P>
<P>
"All we need is to see concrete steps taken on the ground here
in Mogadishu," he said, adding "problems of eight years can't be
solved that easily and the faction leaders are very serious about
their tasks."
</P>
<P>
Mustafa also noted that the Baidoa meeting will of course be
postponed by the Cairo signatories of the Cairo peace deal in
their nearest meeting for the third time. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
