<HEADLINE> Beijing Holds Fair To Employ Retired Armymen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 13 (Xinhua) -- The Beijing municipal government
arranged a fair at the Military Museum today to facilitate
contacts between retired armymen and employing units.
</P>
<P>
In China, the government is responsible for giving jobs to
retired soldiers. The task is heavier in 1998, which is the first
year for the country to cut its army by another 500,000.
</P>
<P>
The municipal government plans to arrange employment for 1,760
demobilized officers this year, an increase of 25 percent over
1997, according to Gao Yunhou, director of the Beijing Municipal
Personnel Bureau.
</P>
<P>
Since 1985, the city has provided jobs to nearly 30,000 people
retiring from the army.
</P>
<P>
Although the capital, like other Chinese cities, faces the
pressing reality of unemployment and redundant government
functionaries, "the municipal government will manage well the
employment of retired officers," Gao said.
</P>
<P>
According to sources with employing units, retired armymen are
popular for they are competent and conscientious about work.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that 583 retired officers reached employment
intentions with employing units today.  
</P>
</TEXT>
