<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Financial Sector Operates Well in First Four Months </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Beijing, May 13 (Xinhua) -- China's financial sector operated
smoothly in the first four months of this year, with the Renminbi
rate remaining stable and bank loans increasing rapidly.
</P>
<P>
Statistics from the People's Bank of China (PBOC) show that, by
the end of April, the total amount of outstanding loans was 7.65
trillion yuan, up 15.2 percent from the same period last year, and
the amount of outstanding loans by state-owned banks was more than
6 trillion yuan, up 14.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
Newly increased loans in the first four months totaled 153.75
billion yuan, of which 151.2 billion yuan came from the last two
months, indicating that banks began to implement their plans for
expanding loans this year.
</P>
<P>
In April, medium- and long-term loans increased 10.76 billion
yuan, reversing the declining trend of the previous three months,
which demonstrated that the series of financial policy
readjustments by the central bank to stimulate domestic demand
have become effective.
</P>
<P>
By the end of April, the amount of outstanding deposits was
8.44 trillion yuan, up 15.5 percent from the same period last
year, of which enterprise deposits accounted for 2.75 trillion
yuan and residents' deposits were 4.9 trillion yuan, up 13.1
percent and 16.3 percent, respectively.
</P>
<P>
According to the statistics, by the end of April, the
outstanding amount of broad money (M2) was 9.27 trillion yuan, up
14.6 percent from the same period last year; while that of narrow
money (M1) was 3.34 trillion yuan, up 11.2 percent; and money in
circulation (M0) was 1.02 trillion yuan, up 9.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the PBOC said that the central bank will
continue to carry out macro-financial regulation in accordance
with changes in the economic and financial development, urge
commercial banks to further improve financial services and ensure
an appropriately fast increase of loans to promote the development
of the national economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
