<HEADLINE> 42 Killed in Election-Related Violence: Ramos </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, May 13 (Xinhua) -- Outgoing Philippine President Fidel
Ramos said here Wednesday that a total of 42 people were killed in
election-related violence as of Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
At a regular press conference held at the Presidential Palace,
he said the death toll went down by 42 percent when compared with
the 73 casualties in the 1995 congressional elections.
</P>
<P>
In the 1992 presidential elections, about 169 people were
killed in various violent incidents.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Ramos also announced that the number of people
injured in various election-related violent incidents fell by 17
percent from 81 in 1995 to 67 this year.
</P>
<P>
However, the total number of election-related violent incidents
went up from 97 in 1995 to 188 during this election, or an
increase of 93.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
These statistics cover the same 150 day period prior to the
1995 polls and the 1998 national and local elections.
</P>
<P>
Ramos had earlier stated that this decrease in deaths and
wounded could mean that there is less use of deadly weapons during
the year's polls.
</P>
<P>
"The number of incidents could be just because of the
fisticuffs or harassment or things of that nature. So, as far as
blood is concerned, there was much less blood spilled during the
1998 elections," he said.
</P>
<P>
There were early reports saying a total of 46 people killed as
of Monday in the elections.
</P>
<P>
About 80 percent of the 34 million registered voters went to
the polls Monday to vote for a new president, a vice president, 12
out of the 24 senators, 260 House representatives and more than
17,000 local officials and councilors.
</P>
<P>
The elections were generally peaceful and orderly, the
Commission on Elections announced after the voting ended.
</P>
<P>
According to the latest unofficial results released by an
accredited private quick-count company, Vice President Joseph
Estrada of the Laban ng Makabayang Masang Pilipino (Fight of
Patriotic Filipino Masses) took a commanding lead. 
</P>
</TEXT>
