<HEADLINE> 3 Iraqi Citizens Jailed by Kuwait Return </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, May 13 (Xinhua) -- Three Iraqis citizens set free by
Kuwait after seven years of imprisonment returned to their
homeland Wednesday, the Iraqi News Agency (INA) reported.
</P>
<P>
INA said that three Iraqis, identified only as Fadhil, 32,
Salem, 30, and Mohammad, 26, are brothers born in Kuwait. They
were detained in 1991 and accused on "false and unrealistic
charges," said INA.
</P>
<P>
They had been handed over to the Iraqi authorities under the
supervision of the International Red Crescent Society, said INA.
</P>
<P>
INA added the three brothers were living in Kuwait because they
were born there and their father, an Iraqi, was a resident in
Kuwait since 1953. They worked in Kuwait before being thrown into
jail.
</P>
<P>
But INA failed to detail the reasons for their detention and
the charges brought against them by the Kuwaitis.
</P>
<P>
According to the brothers, there are more than 35 Iraqi
citizens now being imprisoned in the Central Jail of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
They claimed that in Talha Prison to which they had been
transferred, some prisoners of Iraqi nationalities tried to commit
suicide because they could not bear torture and bad treatment.
</P>
<P>
They called on international humanitarian organizations to
interfere immediately to save those Iraqis who are still in
Kuwaiti prisons. 
