<HEADLINE> Japan Imposes Economic Sanctions on India </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, May 13 (Xinhua) -- Japan applied economic sanctions
against India on Wednesday to protest against the South Asian
nation's latest testing of nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto said Tokyo would
suspend new grants-in-aid to India and shelve the plan to host a
meeting, scheduled for June 30 to July 1, of donor nations to
India.
</P>
<P>
India stunned the world Monday and again Wednesday by
announcing it had conducted a series of underground nuclear tests,
its first since 1974. It said it had the ability to make nuclear
weapons.
</P>
<P>
The three underground nuclear tests Monday involved a fission
device, a low yield device and a thermonuclear device.
</P>
<P>
Japan will also make a formal decision on whether to suspend
yen-denominated official loans to India after monitoring how New
Delhi responds to Japan's concerns over the nuclear tests,
Hashimoto said.
</P>
<P>
Japanese Chief Cabinet Secretary Kanezo Muraoka said in a
statement that the sanctions are based on the principles of
Japan's official development assistance (ODA).
</P>
<P>
Muraoka urged India to stop nuclear tests "immediately" and to
sign the Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty, which has been extended
permanently, and the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty adopted by the
United Nations General Assembly in 1996.
</P>
<P>
India's nuclear testing "can never be tolerated" as it is a
challenge to the efforts by the international community which
seeks a world free from nuclear weapons, Muraoka said.
</P>
<P>
Japan has been the largest aid donor to India since 1986,
providing 3.5 billion yen (about 26.3 million U.S. dollars) in
grants-in-aid to India for fiscal 1997, which ended March 31.
</P>
<P>
In October 1997, Japan committed 132.7 billion yen (about 99.8
million dollars) in loans to India. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980513.0065 </DOCNO>
