<HEADLINE> Sri Lankan Rebels Vow to Fight Against Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, May 13 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka's rebel Liberation
Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE) Wednesday vowed to fight to the death
to defend their controlled territory, according to informed
sources here.
</P>
<P>
In a statement broadcast over his clandestine Voice of Tigers
radio monitored in the north of the country, LTTE leader
Velupillai Prabhakaran said the LTTE members "love their land more
than their lives."
</P>
<P>
Prabhakaran warned that thousands of troops would be killed if
the government persisted in pushing ahead with its operation aimed
at recapturing a 75-km section of the Vavuniya-Jaffna Highway
which runs through the rebel-held territory.
</P>
<P>
The military Tuesday said Operation Jaya Sikuru (Sure of
Victory) launched a year ago would go on till next year.
</P>
<P>
Prabhakaran said the Tigers had been able to stall the military
operation conducted within the jungle region in the north of the
country, according to the sources.
</P>
<P>
The government troops claimed to have recaptured at least 45 km
of the highway and killed over 2,500 rebels, while some 1,400
troops were killed.
</P>
<P>
Prabhakaran said the rebels had lost 1,300 cadres in the past
year, and killed over 3,000 government soldiers and injured 7,000
others.
</P>
<P>
The LTTE rebels have been fighting a war against the government
for a separate state in the north and east of the country since
1983. 
</P>
</TEXT>
