<HEADLINE> Security in South Asia Endangered: Pak Spokesman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, May 13 (Xinhua) -- South Asia has been thrown into
turmoil and "its security has been severely endangered" following
the latest nuclear tests conducted by India, a spokesman for the
Pakistani Foreign Ministry said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
When asked to comment on the two nuclear tests by India
Wednesday, the spokesman said that "these tests have once again
brought into focus the utter contempt in which New Delhi holds the
world public opinion, particularly the non-proliferation efforts."
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that "the latest tests are particularly
provocative as they are by nature aimed at perfection of
battlefield tactical weapons threatening the security of India's
immediate neighbors."
</P>
<P>
"Pakistan once again reiterates that it will take all measures
in consonance with the threat posed to Pakistan's security and the
need for the protection of our national interests," the spokesman
added.
</P>
<P>
According to an announcement by the Indian government, India
conducted two more underground nuclear tests Wednesday in Pokhran
of the northwestern desert state of Rajasthan.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan's Foreign Minister Gohar Ayub Khan has strongly
condemned India for "its highly irresponsible act" of pressing
ahead with its nuclear tests. 
</P>
