<HEADLINE> Russian Mideast Envoy Arrives in Beirut </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, May 13 (Xinhua) -- Russian special Middle East envoy
Viktor Posuvalyuk arrived here Wednesday in a two-day visit aimed
at helping revive the Lebanese and Syrian peace talks with Israel,
stalled for over two years.
</P>
<P>
Upon his arrival at the Beirut International Airport,
Posuvalyuk told reporters that his country will continue
cooperation with the United States and Europe in an effort to seek
a comprehensive peace deal in the region.
</P>
<P>
He also reiterated Russia's support for Lebanon's position in
the Middle East peace process, especially on the Israeli offer of
conditional withdrawal from south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Israel in April decided to endorse the United Nations Security
Council Resolution 425 and said it was ready to withdraw from
south Lebanon if Beirut provided security guarantees for the
Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon rejected the offer, saying the resolution called for an
immediate and unconditional withdrawal and there should be no
negotiations over the pullout.
</P>
<P>
Israel set up a 1,200-square-kilometer security zone in south
Lebanon in 1985 with the claimed aim of protecting its northern
areas from Lebanese guerrilla cross-border attacks.
</P>
<P>
During his stay, the Russian envoy will hold talks with
Lebanese Foreign Minister Farez Boueiz on regional affairs,
especially the Israeli withdrawal offer.
</P>
<P>
He will also convey a message from Russian Foreign Minister
Yevgeny Primakov to Boueiz.
</P>
<P>
After visiting Lebanon, Posuvalyuk will go to Damascus and
confer with Syrian leaders over the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Syria, a power-broker which has 40,000 troops in Lebanon, seeks
a comprehensive peace deal with Israel, which will include the
return of the Golan Heights Israel captured from Syria in the 1967
Middle East war. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
