<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hepatitis C Victims Sue Iran's Blood Transfusion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, May 13 (Xinhua) -- Some 5,000 hepatitis C victims have
filed suits against Iran's Blood Transfusion Organization (BTO),
the daily Jomhuri Islami (Islamic Republic) reported on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Director of the BTO's Research and Refinement Company Kheir
Abadi announced on Tuesday that the country's judiciary is
investigating the complaints of the 5,000 hepatitis C patients,
who received the disease from infected blood products provided by
the BTO.
</P>
<P>
Without mentioning whether the BTO should be responsible for
infection cases, the official said that measures must be adopted
to provide these patients with costly prescription until those
responsible for the damage are identified and compensation
demanded.
</P>
<P>
Abadi put the number of hepatitis C patients at 300,000 in the
country, saying that thousands of patients had been infected with
the disease through transfusions of blood imported from a French
company but they have not filed complaints.
</P>
<P>
The victims can receive at least 500 million U.S. dollars
compensation from the French company if they sue it, he added.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports said that some Iranians infected with AIDS
virus through blood transfusion and their relatives also lodged
suit against the BTO.
</P>
<P>
However, the BTO chief Taghi Khani said on Tuesday that blood
products might be infected with some viruses not only in Iran but
worldwide, the newspaper Iran Daily reported on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The first case of AIDS in Iran was recorded in 1985 when a
one-year-old baby was found to have received the disease from a
transfusion of imported blood. According to the official figure,
around 1,230 Iranian have been diagnosed as carries of the HIV
virus. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
