<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S.Korean Banks' Non-performing Loans Hit $20 Billion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, May 13 (Xinhua) -- The portion of non-performing loans
held by 26 South Korean commercial banks stood at 28.44 trillion
won (about 20.49 billion U.S. dollars) at the end of March, the
highest since 1990, says the Banking Supervisory Authority.
</P>
<P>
The figure showed a rise of six percent from the end of last
year, shortly after South Korea reached out for a rescue loan of
57 billion U.S. dollars from the International Monetary Fund in
December.
</P>
<P>
Non-performing loans in the financiall crisis-engulfed nation
are defined as the sum of bad loans and substandard loans.
</P>
<P>
Among the commercial banks, the Seoul Bank and the Korea First
Bank have piled up the largest portions of the non-pefroming
loans, 13.6 percent and 13 percent of the total respectively.
</P>
<P>
The two banks will be sold to foreigners after the South Korean
government recapitalizes them. 
</P>
</TEXT>
