<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan Holds Meeting on Indian Nuclear Tests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, May 13 (Xinhua) -- The Defense Committee of the
Cabinet of Pakistan met here Wednesday to take stock of the
situation arising from Indian nuclear tests and "overt
weaponization by India."
</P>
<P>
The meeting chaired by Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif concluded
that the "reckless and highly provocative actions" by the Indian
government dealt a severe blow to global non-proliferation, said a
statement issued by the committee Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
India conducted two more nuclear test blasts on Wednesday
following three explosions on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Indian actions had fundamentally altered the strategic
situation and further heightened the tension in South Asia, the
statement said.
</P>
<P>
It said that the Indian actions have magnified the immediacy
and the magnitude of the threat to Pakistan's security.
</P>
<P>
The meeting regretted that Pakistan's warnings to the
international community, particularly major powers, to stop India
from crossing the threshold had gone unheeded, according to the
statement.
</P>
<P>
The statement also said that some countries had sought to bring
"unjustifiable pressure and sanctions" on Pakistan, despite its
impeccable record of utmost restraint.
</P>
<P>
"The responsibility for demolishing the prospects of a
nuclear-free South Asia rested clearly with India and with those
who had adopted a deferential approach and sought to either ignore
or acquiesce in India's blatant attempts to cross the nuclear
threshold," said the statement.
</P>
<P>
It said the meeting affirmed the government's determination to
"reject any unilateral, selective and discriminatory pressure from
any quarter on matters pertaining to national security."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the meeting reiterated Pakistan's resolve to take
all steps it deemed necessary for national security, which were
within its sovereign rights for self-defense.
</P>
<P>
"After comprehensively evaluating the country's defense
preparedness, the meeting expressed satisfaction over Pakistan's
ability to respond effectively and adequately to the new threats
and challenges," the statement said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
