<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India Conducts Two More Nuclear Tests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, May 13 (Xinhua) -- India conducted two more
underground nuclear tests Wednesday in Pokhran of the northwest
desert state of Rajasthan, the Indian government announced.
</P>
<P>
A just-released government statement said the two sub-kiloton
nuclear blasts were carried out at 12:21 local time in
continuation of the planned program of nuclear tests which began
on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The tests have been carried out to generate additional data for
improved computer simulation of designs and for attaining the
capability to carry out subcritical experiments, if considered
necessary, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
It said that the tests were fully contained with no release of
radioactivity into the atmosphere, adding that the blasts
completed the planned series of tests.
</P>
<P>
The statement said that the government of India reiterated the
offer to consider adhering to some of the undertakings in the
Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty, in the framework of the proposal in
its statement Monday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
