<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gro Harlem Brundtland Elected New WHO Director-General </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, May 13 (Xinhua) -- Dr Gro Harlem Brundtland was elected
here Wednesday the new Director-General of the World Health
Organization (WHO).
</P>
<P>
The 59-year-old Norwegian was formally elected at the plenary
session of the 51st World Health Assembly, WHO's highest governing
body. She was nominated as Director-General by the WHO Executive
Board last January.
</P>
<P>
Ms Brundtland will not assume office until July when her
predecessor Dr Hiroshi Nakajima will leave the post which he has
been holding for 10 years.
</P>
<P>
As a medical doctor and Master of Public Health, Ms Brundtland
spend 10 years as physician and scientist in her country's public
health system. For more than 20 years she was in public office,
10 of them as prime minister.
</P>
<P>
Throughout her political career, Ms Brundtland has developed a
growing concern for issues of global significance. In 1983, she was
invited by the then United Nations secretary general to establish
and chair the World Commission on environment and Development.
</P>
<P>
The commission published its report, Our Common Future, in April,
1987. Its recommendations led to the Earth Summit, the UN Conference
on Environment and Development (UNCED) in Rio de Janeiro in 1992.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980513.0082 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Close Lower Despite Higher Dow Jones </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, May 13 (Xinhua) -- The Australian share market lost
ground Wednesday in Sydney with New York's higher close overnight
failing to inspire local investors.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries shed 13.2 points to close at 2773.7, well
off its early high of 2797.5.
</P>
<P>
"Today was a disappointing one after the Dow's performance and
an unsurprising federal budget," a broker said.
</P>
<P>
"It's difficult to attribute the weakness to one particular
factor. I thought we might have seen a bigger bounce in the
market."
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average rose 70.25 points, or 0.7
percent, to 9161.77 overnight, about 30 points below last Monday's
record finish at 9192.66.
</P>
<P>
Locally, the all industrials finished 15.6 points lower at
4780.0 while the all resources ended 12.4 softer at 1168.9.
</P>
<P>
Australia's telecommunications giant Telstra instalment
receipts topped the turnover Wednesday with 14.17 million traded
at a value of 32.5 million U.S. dollars. The receipts ended steady
at 3.64 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Global miner Rio Tinto shed 25 cents to 21.15 Australian
dollars, and Australia's leading resources company BHP ended eight
weaker at 14.35 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The gold index forfeited 25.9 points or almost two percent to
1295.4 as the price of bullion closed in Sydney at 297.15 U.S.
dollars, down from Tuesday's close of 299.80 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Among the banks, National Australia Bank rose 15 cents to 22.45
Australian dollars after earlier hitting an intra-day peak of
22.75 Australian dollars, Westpac bank improved six cents to 10.75
Australian dollars, Commonwealth Bank of Australia eased seven
cents to 18.93 Australian dollars and ANZ bank dipped two cents to
11.45 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Australia's fifth largest bank, St George, rallied 20 cents to
close at 9.97 Australian dollars after Tuesday unveiling a 45.95
percent lift in first half net profit to 91.7 million U.S.
dollars.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was 337.41 million, valued at 657 million
U.S. dollars, with falls outpacing rises 620 to 453. 
</P>
