<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish Firms Welcomed to Join in Romania's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, May 13 (Xinhua) -- Turkish enterprises should actively
participate in Romania's ambitious privatization program, thus
pushing Turkish-Romanian cooperation to a new high, Romanian
Senate Speaker Petre Roman has said.
</P>
<P>
In an exclusive interview with Turkish newspaper Daily News,
which is published Wednesday, Roman said that a large number of
Romanian state-owned energy, telecommunications and tourism firms
will be sold in the next two years.
</P>
<P>
The government plans to raise 800 million U.S. dollars through
the privatization program this year, he said.
</P>
<P>
"The opportunities are now opening up and I am certain that
direct Turkish investments will double or triple in the coming
years," Roman said.
</P>
<P>
The trade volume of Turkey and Romania totaled 750 million
dollars in 1997 and Turkish direct investment in Romania stood at
150 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Turkey mainly exports synthetic fibre, machines, plastics,
grains and processed food to Romania and imports fertilizer,
edible oil, aluminium, iron and steel products from Romania.
</P>
<P>
According to official figures, some 5,000 Turkish state and
private enterprises have invested in the eastern European country
in industries of brewing, banking and finance, tourism as well as
soft drinks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
