<HEADLINE> New Director-General Calls for WHO Reforms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, May 13 (Xinhua) -- The World Health Organization (WHO)
should carry out reforms in order to tackle challenges in front of
the organization, said newly-elected Director-General of the World
Health Organization (WHO) here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"WHO can and must change," Dr Gro Harlem Brundtland said in a
speech immediately after her election at the 51st World Health
Assembly.
</P>
<P>
"It must become more effective, more accountable, more
transparent and more receptive to a changing world," the
59-year-old Norwegian stressed.
</P>
<P>
She urged WHO member states to "take responsibility for the
targets they set and provide resources", adding that "they must
practise what they preach from this rostrum".
</P>
<P>
In transition from one century to another, Brundtland said, WHO
member states should forge stronger relations to face changes
which will be faster and more dramatic from an economic, social
and health perspective.
</P>
<P>
"The world is in transition," she said. "So accordingly WHO
must be in transition. Looking ahead."
</P>
<P>
Ms Brundtland, former Norwegian prime minister, will not assume
office until July when her predecessor Dr Hiroshi Nakajima will
leave the post which he has been holding for 10 years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
