<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-13 11:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Cabinet Approves Investment Plan to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, May 13 (Xinhua) -- The Israeli cabinet has approved
a Finance Ministry plan to fight unemployment by investing 1
billion shekels (about 270 million U.S. dollars) in
infrastructure, Israel Radio reported on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The report said that the plan was endorsed by a vote of 12 to 4
after more than six hours of stormy debate in the cabinet Tuesday
night.
</P>
<P>
The investments, which will be financed by budget cuts,
include 800 million shekels (216 million dollars) for constructing
new roads and upgrading existing highways, 120 million shekels
(32.5 million dollars) for building new train stations and
railways, and the rest for renovating slum neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the new investments, the plan also calls for
legislation to reduce the number of foreign workers and
administrative steps to remove bureaucratic impediments to
economic activity.
</P>
<P>
Both Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and Bank of
Israel Governor Jacob Frenkel strongly supported the plan.
</P>
<P>
Frenkel said investment in infrastructure was one of the best
ways to stimulate economic growth and increase employment in the
long run.
</P>
<P>
The plan, however, was blasted by some ministers. Industry and
Trade Minister Natan Sharansky charged that the plan would not
promote economic growth because it would not help the country's
main growth engine -- the high-tech sector.
</P>
<P>
What this sector needs, Sharansky said, is more research and
development funds.
</P>
<P>
Due to the slowdown of economic growth, the unemployment
problem has become more and more serious in Israel.
</P>
<P>
At the end of February, the unemployment rate hit 8.3 percent,
the highest since 1993. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
