<HEADLINE> Share Prices Plummet on Singapore Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, May 13 (Xinhua) -- Share prices plummeted on the
Singapore market as the benchmark Straits Times Industrials Index
(STII) declined sharply by 68.07 points to close at 1331.98 points
on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said that stock prices plunged by 4.9 percent on an
upsurge of violence in Indonesia and active selling of several
index-linked stocks. They said that there was a loss of confidence
in the region.
</P>
<P>
Fears of weak domestic corporate earnings and a slowdown in the
Singapore economy also dented sentiment, they added.
</P>
<P>
Total market volume increased to 161.39 million units, valued
at 291.56 million Singapore dollars (about 176.7 million U.S.
dollars). Declines overwhelmed advances by 323 to 33, while 238
other counters remained unchanged.
</P>
<P>
Guthrie Warrant02 was the most actively traded counter as it
registered a turnover of 11.24 million units. It was followed by
Singapore Telecom which had 7.25 million shares traded. Singapore
Technologies (ST) Engineering was next with 6.94 million shares
changed hands.
</P>
<P>
Local computer sound card maker Creative 50 led the gainers of
the day as it rose by 60 cents to finish at 31.4 Singapore
dollars. MISC Foreign increased by 24 cents to end at 2.9
Singapore dollars, while NatElec was up by 13 cents to close at
3.04 Singapore dollars.
</P>
<P>
On the downside, Transmarco was the biggest loser as it
declined by 1.3 dollars to end at 4.9 Singapore dollars. SPH
(Singapore Press Holdings) fell by 1.2 Singapore dollars to close
at 14.4 dollars. RothmansI lost 65 cents to finish at 7.15
Singapore dollars. 
</P>
