<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Eighty Percent South Koreans Suffer Pay Cuts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, May 13 (Xinhua) -- About 80 percent of South Koreans
have suffered pay cuts since the nation signed with the
International Monetary Fund for a 57-billion-U.S. dollar economic
bailout loan last December.
</P>
<P>
Under a survey conducted by the Korea Chamber of Commerce and
Industry Wednesday, of the 800 people polled, 76.5 percent
experienced drops in household incomes, with an average reduction
rate of 32 percent.
</P>
<P>
Only 22.9 percent of the respondents said their earnings
remained unchanged while less than one in every 100 respondents,
or 0.6 percent, reported increases in income.
</P>
<P>
The low and middle-income brackets were the hardest hit.
</P>
<P>
Almost 90 percent of the low-income people earning less than
one million won (about 714 U.S. dollars) a month, and 80.6 percent
of the middle-income earners whose monthly income ranges from one
million to two million won, suffered pay cuts while among the
high-income bracket earning more than three million won a month,
only 58.9 percent reported pay reduction, said the survey.
</P>
<P>
With respect to the pay-reduction scope, the low and
middle-income families reported 45.8 percent and 32.8 percent,
respectively, whereas the high-income ones answered 24.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
Harsh economic times are giving enormous pains to the poor and
destroying the middle class while the wealthy people are getting
even richer as banks offer sky-high interest rates, said the
survey. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
