<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK To Host China Investment Policy Seminar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, May 13 (Xinhua) -- High-ranking officials from the
Chinese Central government will be in Hong Kong next month to give
an update on the Chinese mainland's investment climate and
economic policy at the '98 China Investment Policy Seminar.
</P>
<P>
Jointly organized by the Chinese Ministry of Foreign Trade and
Economic Cooperation (MOFTEC) and the Hong Kong Trade Development
Council (TDC), the seminar will be held on June 2 at the Hong Kong
Convention &AMP; Exhibition Center.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference here Wednesday, TDC Deputy Executive
Director Dennis Yau said new economic policies are coming on
stream since the 15th Congress of the Chinese Communist Party last
autumn, which opened up lots of business opportunities for Hong
Kong companies.
</P>
<P>
"The mainland market will be opened up further to the outside
world, and foreign investors are encouraged to take part in
various projects covering agriculture, infrastructure, pillar
industries, and those requiring high technology," said Yau.
</P>
<P>
The seminar will provide an insight into trade and investment
topics, he continued, adding these first-hand information is vital
to investors interested in tapping the markets in China's mainland
areas.
</P>
<P>
Joining Yau at the press conference was MOFTEC's Director
General of Foreign Investment Administration Mrs. Ma Xiuhong, who
hoped that the seminar would enhance the understanding of the
investment environment in China's mainland areas and promote the
direct investment of local firms, and overseas firms doing
business in Hong Kong and in the mainland areas.
</P>
<P>
Speakers at the seminar will be from China's key state
ministries and they will speak on the opening of China's financial
market, state-owned enterprises reform, latest customs policies
and regulations, and prospects of China's economic development and
priority projects, Ma said.
</P>
<P>
The seminar will be held in conjunction with the '98 China
(Hong Kong) Investment Symposium, to be organized by the MOFTEC
from June 2 to 5.
</P>
<P>
Led by MOFTEC Assistant Minister An Min, a delegation
representing more than 20 provinces, autonomous regions,
municipalities and cities will bring some 700 investment projects
to the symposium, which enters its fifth year this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
