<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Policing of Hong Kong Unchanged after Handover </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, May 13 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong Police have
continued to enforce the law after the handover in exactly the
same way as before, fairly, impartially and professionally, said
the Commissioner of Police in a book published here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In his foreword in the Police Review 1997 published here
Wednesday, Commissioner of Police Eddie Hui Ki-on wrote that many
people were concerned at the beginning of 1997 about how Hong Kong
would be policed after July 1, 1997.
</P>
<P>
The fact is business as usual -- public demonstrations
continued, the handover did not affect policing and there was no
exodus of senior officers from the police force, he said.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, only 156 officers left the police force, and the vast
majority of expatriate officers remained committed to Hong Kong
and the force.
</P>
<P>
The Commissioner noted that the overall crime rate for 1997
continued to drop to hit the lowest in 24 years. In 1997, the
overall number of crimes recorded dropped by 15 percent from the
previous year, with a marked decrease in burglaries and robberies.
</P>
</TEXT>
