<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Closes Sharply Down on Asia, Gold </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, May 13 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar slumped to a
12-year low Wednesday, pushed lower by selling by Asian traders,
with the softer gold bullion price also weighing on the currency.
</P>
<P>
After diving through the 63 U.S. cent mark in early European
trade, the local currency was trading at 62.90 U.S. cents
Wednesday, from 63.56 U.S. cents at Tuesday's close.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar traded in a narrow band of 63.15 to 63.35
U.S. cents for most of the local session before falling further in
early European trading.
</P>
<P>
Stuart Moore, foreign exchange manager with St. George Bank,
said the Australian dollar was driven lower by weak Asian
currencies and a fall in the price of gold.
</P>
<P>
In New York, COMEX gold for current delivery closed at 298.9
U.S. dollars per ounce, down 2.3 U.S. dollars from the previous
COMEX close.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese yen weakened in offshore trading Tuesday night,
contributing to the sell-off of the Australian dollar, but had
strengthened slightly during local trade.
</P>
<P>
Moore said the surplus of 1.7 billion U.S. dollars unveiled
Tuesday night in the Australian federal budget for 1998-1999 had
initially seen the Australian dollar rally a little.
</P>
<P>
"It wasn't until later when New York walked back in that they
sold it back off again.
</P>
<P>
"So the budget really didn't have a big impact on it," he said.
</P>
<P>
Also at the close, the Australian dollar was at 84.63 Japanese
yen, from 84.65 yen Tuesday, and at 1.1218 Deutsche marks from
1.1298 marks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
