<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain Urges Press not to Incite World Cup Hate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 13 (Xinhua) -- British newspapers were urged on
Wednesday not to incite violence or disorder during the World Cup
in France next month.
</P>
<P>
In a statement sent to all newspaper editors, Britain's press
watchdog Press Complaints Commission Chairman Lord Wakeham said
robust reporting of the competition was desired, but incitement of
violence was not.
</P>
<P>
"What we don't want is there to be -- perhaps by accident --
incitement to violence, incitement to disorder (which would) put
the fans at risk and put the players at risk," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We're just reminding newspaper editors to be extremely careful
about this... self-regulation requires them to exercise a proper
degree of restraint," he added.
</P>
<P>
British newspapers have mounted attacks on the way ticket
allocations were handled, accusing the French of grabbing the vast
majority of seats.
</P>
<P>
Two months ago, the tabloid Daily Star was criticized for
attacks on the sharing of tickets for the tournament under the
headline "Frogs need a good kicking."
</P>
<P>
But Wakeham added he was sure most newspapers wanted to report
fairly on the World Cup tournament and take pride in the English
and Scottish teams which have qualified for the cup's finals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
