<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Withdraws Support for Mozambique's Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, May 13 (Xinhua) -- The United States will withdraw its
support for the local elections scheduled to be held in 33 cities
and towns in Mozambique, the U.S. embassy in Maputo has
announced.
</P>
<P>
The press release issued here Tuesday by the U.S. embassy here
said the U.S. government regretted that most of the opposition
parties including the largest Mozambican National Resistance
(RENAMO) had boycotted the elections, the Noticias newspaper
reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The United States felt regret that the demands of the
opposition for fairness and transparency received no response
from the government and the series of legislations on polls
passed by parliament last year, the release said.
</P>
<P>
Under such circumstances, the U.S. decided not to provide
support for the elections in Mozambique any longer, it said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. government believes that what is important for the
democratic process in the southern African nation is that any
individual or political party should not violate or deprive the
voting rights of the citizens, it noted.
</P>
<P>
The release said any kind of local elections which lack
maximum participation of citizens with different political views
would damage the international image of Mozambique and represent
a setback in the democratic process.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. government called on the Mozambican government and
the opposition parties to work together for a consensus on the
basis of flexibility and compromise when they begin to draft and
pass new laws concerning the general election in 1999.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the position of the United States, Mozambican
Minister of State Administration Alfredo Gamito said Tuesday
night that the withdrawal of the U.S. support will have no impact
on the elections because his government has made all
organizational and financial preparations in a bid to hold the
elections as scheduled. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980513.0111 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> G-15 Calls for World Attention on Developing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, May 11 (Xinhua) -- The Group of 15 (G-15) Wednesday
called on the international community to address pressing problems
facing developing countries, particularly the poorest in Africa.
</P>
<P>
The call was made in a joint communique issued at the end of
the three-day G-15 summit here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The summit was chaired by Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak and
attended, among other leaders, by presidents of Indonesia, Kenya,
Algeria, Zimbabwe and Senegal.
</P>
<P>
During the summit, the leaders discussed how to boost
South-South cooperation and South-North dialog, believing such
cooperation will help avoid future financial crises like the one
in Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
The leaders called for an appropriate global response to deal
with both the financial crisis in Southeast Asia and the
strengthening of regional and international cooperation in
managing such crises in the future.
</P>
<P>
The communique said that "it is imperative that in facing the
current crisis, the attention of the international community is
not diverted from pressing problems facing developing countries
and least developed countries in particular, the majority of which
are in Africa."
</P>
<P>
It noted that "the financial crisis in East and Southeast Asia
is not an isolated or an unprecedented phenomenon. Financial
crises have been occurring with greater frequency in both
developed and developing countries with severe impact on growth,
employment and development."
</P>
<P>
The communique said that the leaders realized the need for
continued consultation and cooperation among developing countries
in exchanging experiences on dealing with the implications of the
financial crisis and avoiding future ones.
</P>
<P>
"There is also a need for greater dialog between the developed
and developing countries on a systematic basis to address the
challenges posed by the rapidly integrating financial markets and
expanding international capital flows," it added.
</P>
<P>
The next G-15 summit will be held in Jamaica next year.
</P>
<P>
As a grouping of developing countries from Latin America,
Africa and Asia, the G-15 was founded in 1989 with the aim of
promoting economic and trade cooperation among the member states
and boosting cooperation among developing countries.
</P>
<P>
The 16 members of the group are Algeria, Argentina, Brazil,
Chile, Egypt, India, Indonesia, Jamaica, Kenya, Malaysia, Mexico,
Nigeria, Peru, Senegal, Venezuela, and Zimbabwe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
