<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Korea's Garment Export Surging </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, May 13 (Xinhua) -- South Korea's apparel exports grew
11.3 percent to 830 million U.S. dollars in the first three months
of this year, the first quarterly rise since 1989.
</P>
<P>
The growth, the Korean International Trade Association said
Wednesday, is expected to last through the year as orders from
Hong Kong and Russia are 50 percent higher than normal.
</P>
<P>
The association attributed the growth mainly to aggressive
efforts by local manufactures to make up losses at the home market
and lower price of clothing brought by the devalued won.
</P>
<P>
The three months also saw a brisker garment export to the
United States, which had reduced its quota of imports from China.
</P>
<P>
South Korea's garment export kept a double-digit rise before
the 1990s and accounted for 14 percent of the nation's exports.
In 1989, it sold 8.7 billion dollars worth of clothes overseas.
</P>
<P>
However, since then, South Korean-made clothes have been slowly
elbowed out of the international market by other Asian countries,
which are able to provide apparel of cheaper and better quality.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, the country's garment export was down to 3.9 billion
dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
