<DOCNO> XIE19980513.0117 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Over 9,000 Crows Killed by Dar Residents </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, May 13 (Xinhua) -- Dar es Salaam has launched a
massive campaign to kill disagreeable Indian crows, The Guardian
said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Since February, more than 9,000 Indian crows have been trapped
and killed in the city, the newspaper quoted an official of the
Wildlife Conservation Society of Tanzania (WCST) as saying.
</P>
<P>
The WCST Conservation Officer, Paul Nyiti, said with the aid
of the Canadian Fund for Local Initiative, people have used
special traps made of wire mesh and timber to kill the crows.
Each trap is able to catch 40 to 50 crows.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the harm done by the crows, Nyiti said that the
crows have stolen people's food and valuable items such as golden
chains.
</P>
<P>
People are also worried about the spread of rubbish by the
crows which cause transmission of diseases. They also complained
about the noise made by the crows.
</P>
<P>
He said that the crows are not only aggressive predators to
domestic poultry but also to native bird species while the crows
themselves have no natural enemy.
</P>
<P>
Nyiti said the crows originated from Asia and were introduced
in the Zanzibar isles one century ago. They were brought to Dar
es Salaam around 1955 by unknown people.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a crow control team has appealed to residents
living close to the trap sites to contribute scrap food as bait.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
