<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pak Trade Deficit Declines Drastically in 10 Months </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, May 13 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan's trade deficit has
declined drastically by 1.57 billion U.S. dollars in the first ten
months of the 1997-98 fiscal year (July 1-June 30) compared to the
same period of the previous fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
Commerce Minister Ishaq Dar told the reporters here Wednesday
that the decline in trade deficit is "unprecedented in the history
of the country."
</P>
<P>
The government had set the target to reduce the trade deficit
by one billion dollars in the whole 1997-98 fiscal year, but the
deficit squeezed by 1.57 billion dollars in just ten months which
is beyond the target, Dar said.
</P>
<P>
The Minister said, the biggest menace facing Pakistan's economy
was the balance of payment problem and the trade deficit.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan's overall deficit in 1996-97 fiscal year was 4.4
billion dollars, out of which the trade deficit was 3.57 billion
dollars.
</P>
<P>
The trade deficit in 1993-94, 1994-95 and 1995-96 was 1.76
billion dollars, 2.25 billion dollars and 3.1 billion dollars
respectively.
</P>
<P>
Dar said that Pakistan's export increased by 16 percent in
rupee terms during the first 10 months of the current fiscal year
to have reached a volume of 306 billion rupees (6.97 billion U.S.
dollars) compared to the same period of the last fiscal year which
were 264 billion rupees (six billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Pakistan's import in the same period remained at 376
billion rupees (8.54 billion dollars), showing a reduction of 3.8
percent compared to the same period of the previous fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
The Minister said Pakistan's economy started to show signs of
up-turn in the first ten months of the 1997-98 fiscal year, owing
to the economic reform packages initiated by the present
government.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
