<HEADLINE> Rural Social Security Computer System Being Tried out in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 13 (Xinhua) -- China began experimenting with a
rural social security computer system recently, sponsored by the
Chinese Ministry of Civil Affairs and the U.S.'s John Hancock
Mutual Life Insurance Company, for the purpose of setting up a
nationwide rural social security computer network.
</P>
<P>
It is being tried in the cities of Dalian in northeastern
Liaoning Province, and Yantai and Laizhou in east China's Shandong
Province.
</P>
<P>
The system will play an important role in developing rural
social security management, and in improving information
exchanges, a civil affairs ministry official said. It can also
provide help in establishing a nationwide management system in the
future.
</P>
<P>
John Hancock is one of the largest life insurers in the world,
with representative offices in Beijing, Tianjin and Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
The company will invite officials from the People's Bank of
China, the State Development Planning Commission, and the Ministry
of Finance for a study tour in the United States this September,
so that these officials will be given a look at the life insurance
and pension system in the United States.  
</P>
</TEXT>
