<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Officials Discuss Land Use Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 13 (Xinhua) -- China's top legislature today
organized a discussion of amendments to the Land-Use Law by
officials from the State Development Planning Commission, Ministry
of Land and Natural Resources, Ministry of Agriculture, and other
offices.
</P>
<P>
The chairmen of relevant special committees of the National
People's Congress (NPC) also attended the discussion.
</P>
<P>
The NPC Standing Committee decided earlier this month to
publish the amendments, which will have a direct effect on all
Chinese, and solicit opinions from the public.
</P>
<P>
The amendments emphasize farmland protection, said Qu Geping
and Wang Chaowen, who are members of the NPC Standing Committee.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Huaixi, who is a member of the NPC Standing Committee,
suggested that the revised law should set a minimal level for per
capita farmland in China, in accordance with international
practices.
</P>
<P>
The 71-article draft deals with protection of farmland
resources and prevents farmland from being used for other purposes.
</P>
<P>
China adopted a land-use law in 1986, but the existing law is
considered unsuitable for a market economy.
</P>
<P>
The NPC Standing Committee unanimously approved the public
discussion of the amendments and Chinese citizens can express their
opinions through certain government offices. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980513.0128 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Financial Sector Plays Significant Role in Economic Growth (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Analysts say that the central government measures to stimulate
the economy allow ample room for the financial sector and demand
much of it. It will continue an appropriately tight monetary
policy and make minor adjustments when needed, and increase the
money supply to ensure sufficient credit for economic growth.
</P>
<P>
This January, the People's Bank of China (PBOC) published a
series of reform measures, including lifting the ceiling on
commercial bank loans, changing the deposit reserve system, and
lowering interest rates. These measures improved the commercial
banks' loan strength and helped divert funds to new economic
growth areas.
</P>
<P>
Under the central bank policies, the four state-owned
commercial banks and three policy banks announced their expanded
credit plans in April. The Construction Bank said it will channel
100 billion yuan into state-backed key development areas, and the
Industrial and Commercial Bank will put a large part of its 200
billion yuan in new loans into these areas. In addition, the PBOC
is continuing the financial opening up to attract more foreign
capital.
</P>
<P>
Analysts say China is undergoing a transition from a planned
to a market economy, the success of which is critical for
reaching its growth target, and the financial sector plays a
decisive role in this. No reforms, from state enterprise to
employment, can do without the financial sector.
</P>
<P>
As the commercialization of state-owned banks progresses, the
financial sector will put profit in first place and make an effort
to improve credit quality and cut the number of unperforming
loans, a move that will help adjust the industrial structure,
prevent construction duplication, and lead economic development in
a healthy direction.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980513.0129 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Reports Sharp Rise in 1997 Trade Surplus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, May 13 (Xinhua) -- Japan's trade surplus in fiscal 1997,
which ended March 31, rose for the first time in five years to
13,613.9 billion yen (about 102.3 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The surplus, due to an increase in exports and a slowdown in
imports, was up 55 percent from that of the previous year, said
the Finance Ministry Wednesday in a preliminary report.
</P>
<P>
Boosted by the weakness of yen and strong overseas demands,
exports advanced by 11.3 percent, the first double-digit rise in
eight years, to 49,893.0 billion yen (375.1 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
In contrast, said the report, Japan's imports slowed with a
slight year-on-year increase of 0.6 percent to 36,279.1 billion
yen (272.8 billion dollars), because of the weak domestic demand.
</P>
<P>
Of the overall favorable balance, the surplus in goods and
services trade in fiscal 1997 totaled 7,340.9 billion yen (55.2
billion dollars), nearly four times that in the previous year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
