<DOCNO> XIE19980513.0130 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Private Sector Growing Fast in Guangdong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, May 13 (Xinhua) -- The private sector in south China
economic powerhouse of Guangdong Province has maintained an
average annual rise of some 20 percent in the past few years, and
is contributing more to local economic growth.
</P>
<P>
By last year, the province had more than 1.53 million
privately-run pop- and -mom shops and larger-scale businesses,
with 126.3 billion yuan in registered capital, and employing 4.2
million people. The sector turned in 7.1 billion yuan in taxes in
1997.
</P>
<P>
After decade-long extensive operations, most of the private
businesses are making new efforts to further improve management
and turn to the modern enterprise system. As a result, 70 percent
of the sector has been transformed into limited companies.
</P>
<P>
Some 70 percent of the private businesses are involved in the
service sector. However, some have begun to try in other areas,
such as industry, agriculture, financial information services,
hotel management, foreign trade, and hi-tech products.
</P>
<P>
The province now has more than 3,000 science- and
-technology-intensive private enterprises, and those in this
capital developed 400-odd new technologies and products, 32 of
which were given the state patents.
</P>
<P>
Xie Yongxing started with only 3,000 yuan (361 US dollars) in
Xuwen County in 1985. But now he owns a pearl company, which has
some 1,000 workers, and produces over 600 million yuan (72.3
million US dollars) in annual output value as well as more than 20
million US dollars of exports.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the private sector also serves as a major channel to
ease unemployment pressure. Statistics show that the number of
laid-off workers in the province amounted to about 500,000, and
half of them have found new jobs, mostly in private businesses.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
