<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Tibetans Use New Types of Fuel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, May 13 (Xinhua) -- Liquefied petroleum gas, solar cooker
and electric stove are becoming a new vogue of consumption among
residents in the Tibet Autonomous Region in southwest China.
</P>
<P>
At present, eighty percent of urban households in Tibet use
liquefied petroleum gas (LPG) instead of the traditional fuel like
coal and dry cow dung, according to the LPG sales company in the
region.
</P>
<P>
Baibar, a resident in the old city area of Lhasa, capital of
Tibet, was very satisfied with the gas cooker his family installed
recently. He said coal and dry cow dung he used previously for
cooking are quite inconvenient and give off too much fume.
</P>
<P>
Since the 1980, the central government has increased financial
aid to the economic construction in Tibet. The Yamzho Yumco
Hydro-electric power station with a total installed capacity of
90,000 kw was completed last year, basically putting an end of
electricity shortage in areas near Lhasa.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Tibet developed a type of small solar energy stove
for families and a large amount of bottled liquefied petroleum gas
and kerosene was shipped from the inland areas.
</P>
<P>
"Cooking with liquefied petroleum gas costs 45 yuan (5.3 US
dollars) each month, less than 5 percent of my salary," said a
driver working at a government body in Tibet.
</P>
<P>
He also said he and his neighbors would never burn cow dung any
more since they have this new type of fuel.
</P>
<P>
In order to protect the forest and environment, the local
government has poured 53 million yuan to build LPG supplying
project. Farmers and herdsmen in rural areas also began using
LPG. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
