<DOCNO> XIE19980513.0137 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Minister on Economic Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, May 13 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean Finance Minister Herbert
Murerwa has said that government's macro-economic stabilization
program and the sustainability of economic reforms face a crucial
test.
</P>
<P>
The finance minister presented a 17-point ministerial policy
statement to parliament Tuesday on the Zimbabwe Program for
Economic and Social Transformation (1996/2000), the daily Herald
reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"As a result of failure to meet the primary requirement for
macro-economic stability, fiscal balance and a sluggish response
by the productive sectors to the reforms," Murerwa said,"economic
growth only averaged 1.7 percent per annum during the first phase
of reforms (1991/95) against a target of five percent and a
population growth rate of three percent."
</P>
<P>
He said the combined effects of recurrent droughts, high
interests, high inflation, global recession, tight monetary
policies and delays in implementing public sector reforms slowed
down investment, drastically eroded real incomes and consumption
and overshadowed the important progress that had been made in
other areas.
</P>
<P>
But despite these problems, said Murerwa, the reforms had
ushered in a flexible framework for adjustable and progressive
reforms of the economy.
</P>
<P>
The minister explained that the basic philosophy guiding the
new reforms is to achieve a sustained high rate of economic
growth and speedy development in order to raise the incomes and
living standards of the people and expand productive employment
of rural peasants and urban workers.
</P>
<P>
The experiences in the last quarter of 1997, he said, have
underlined the need to urgently restore macro-economic stability,
high growth rate, low inflation and interest rates and a stable
exchange rate.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that there is need to facilitate the public and
private savings and investment needed to attain growth. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
