<DOCNO> XIE19980513.0138 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Financial Sector Playing Important Role in China's Economic Growth (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 13 (Xinhua) -- The latest report on China's
macro-economic condition from the State Development and Planning
Commission shows that financial policies are already having an
effect on economic growth.
</P>
<P>
The report says that, in the first quarter, banks increased
loans, many new construction projects started, real estate
investment began to recover, and housing sales were up 41 percent.
</P>
<P>
After the Chinese government set an economic growth target of 8
percent at the beginning of the year, the financial sector began a
new round of reforms, improved controls, and adjusted its
allocation of credit.
</P>
<P>
Analysts predict that these measures will have an effect in the
third quarter, along with other efforts designed to stimulate
consumer demand, and the slowing growth is expected to be under
control in the second half.
</P>
<P>
The economy has had a "soft landing" in the past few years, but
it also faces a serious challenge from the continued decline in
growth.
</P>
<P>
The Southeast Asian financial crisis has inevitably had a
negative effect on China's exports, one of the major sources of
economic strength, so the central government has designated a
number of new areas for support, to stimulate the economy by
increasing consumer demand.
</P>
<P>
Infrastructure, high-tech industries, technology improvements,
housing construction, and other sectors have been included in the
support list, with the hope that their contribution to the economy
will help the country reach its goal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980513.0139 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Vice-Premier Meets With Angolan Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 13 (Xinhua) -- Vice-premier Qian Qichen, in a
meeting with an Angolese delegation today, said that the Chinese
government supports the African national liberation movement and
appreciates the role Angola played in the continent's liberation
movement, especially its decolonization.
</P>
<P>
He told the group, which is led by Pedro Neto, Angola's
minister of social communications, that China is grateful for
Angola's support of China in international affairs, and that the
Chinese government supports cooperation between the Chinese press
and publishers with Angolan departments. The voice of developing
countries should be heard louder and stronger in the international
community, he said.
</P>
<P>
Qian also recalled his Angolan visit in 1989 and discussed
China's reforms and opening up.
</P>
<P>
Neto said that the two countries have had frequent contacts in
recent years and that he hopes to strengthen the cooperation in
information exchange.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Angolan government adheres to the "one China"
policy and hopes to continue cooperating with China in areas like
human rights.
</P>
<P>
Neto and his party are here at the invitation of China's Press
and Publication Administration. 
</P>
</TEXT>
