<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Telecom Services Remain Poor in W. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, May 13 (Xinhua) -- Telecommunications services in west
Africa have remained the most inefficient in the world despite
huge expenses.
</P>
<P>
Countries in the sub-region spend more than three billion U.S.
Dollars yearly to import telecommunication equipment but the
input has not produced cheerful results, according to Nigerian
Minister of Science and Technology Maj.-Gen. Sam Momah.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, the need for genuine technological and industrial
revolution of the telecommunication industry must be underscored
in the sub-region, the minister said, quoted by the Post Express
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The minister admitted that the task of technological and
industrial breakthrough was "arduous and capital intensive". But
he did not mention what measures should be taken in this effect.
</P>
<P>
Earlier communications Minister Maj.-Gen. Patrick Aziza said
Nigeria needed six billion Dollars to increase its telephone
accessibility from 0.46 lines per 100 people to one for every 100
people as prescribed by the International Telecommunications
Union.
</P>
<P>
For Africa as a whole, a minimum of 20 million lines will be
installed by the turn of this century, according to the Africa
Telecom '98 which just concluded in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
This will leave more work for African countries to do to meet
the target. 
</P>
</TEXT>
