<HEADLINE> Beijing Seminar On Urban Traffic, Environment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 13 (Xinhua) -- City officials from Gothenburg,
Sweden, met with Beijing officials today at a seminar to discuss
urban traffic and environment problems, something that Beijing
needs to learn more about.
</P>
<P>
Anders Sundstrom, Sweden's Minister of Industry, who is in
China on an official visit, presided over the opening ceremony of
the two-day seminar. It is being attended by Swedish officials and
members of the Volvo Group, a natural gas motor vehicle
manufacturer, and Chinese officials and scientists.
</P>
<P>
The Gothenburg representatives brought with them a bus, a car
and a dumptruck that run on natural gas and gave their Chinese
hosts a demonstration ride in the downtown area.
</P>
<P>
Beijing is interested in introducing natural gas motor vehicles
to reduce air pollution. Last year, the city ruled that motor
vehicles must use lead-free gasoline.
</P>
<P>
China is becoming increasingly aware of the use of natural gas
and other fuels to replace gasoline. Chongqing, once one of the
worst polluted cities in China, is a pioneer in the use of natural
gas vehicles. The city plans to have all of its buses and tax cabs
running on natural gas in future.  
</P>
</TEXT>
