<HEADLINE> Japan, Mongolia Aiming at Closer Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, May 13 (Xinhua) -- Mongolian President Natsagiin
Bagabandi and Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto agreed
here Wednesday to promote bilateral cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was reached during a 30-minute meeting between
the two, Japanese government officials said.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Bagabandi, who arrived here Monday for a
five-day official visit, said his country will carry out economic
reform programs in cooperation with Japan.
</P>
<P>
He also hoped to attract more investment from Japan.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto told Bagabandi that Japan backs Mongolia's bid to
join the ASEAN Regional Forum, a grouping on security issues among
members of the Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) and
their dialogue partners.
</P>
<P>
In addition, he offered Japan's support for Mongolia's bid to
participate in the Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation (APEC) forum.
</P>
<P>
In a joint statement issued after the meeting, the two sides
affirmed the policies of establishing a comprehensive partnership
through promotion of mutual understanding and trust. 
</P>
