<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Central China City Builds Agriculture Project with WB Loans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HEFEI, May 13 (Xinhua) -- Fuyang, an agriculture-oriented city
in east China's Anhui Province, has completed a World
Bank-credited project on improving agricultural facilities.
</P>
<P>
A WB official said, after his inspection tour of the project,
that Fuyang people's effort along with World Bank's capital
assistance has resulted in satisfactary achievements.
</P>
<P>
Under the project, 140,000 ha. of medium and low yielding land
or 13 percent of the total farmland in the city have been upgraded
to double the per unit yield of grain and cash crops, which means
more than four time the farmers' capita income.
</P>
<P>
Total investment for the project approximates 800 million yuan
(96 million U.S. dollars) with 44.58 million U.S. dollars of WB
loans and the rest channeled by the city government.
</P>
<P>
Sixty percent of the fund was spent on building an irrigation
and drainage network for improving the circulation of irrigation
water. This includes building or renovating 28 pumping stations,
1,185 draining stations and 100 km-long leaking-proof ditches in
addition to digging 6,415 wells and excavating 36.8 million
cu.m. of earth.
</P>
<P>
Another priority has been given to building shelter-forest
belt. With the project funding, the forest coverage of the city
has grown from 10.5 percent before the launching of the project to
the present 17.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
The introduction of agro hi-tech during the period has also
contributed to improved soil quality, with which the city has set
up 10 high-yield production bases.
</P>
<P>
Fuyang is the largest agricultural city in this major grain
production province in east China with 12 million people engaged
in farming and its farmland acreage accounting for one percent of
the country's total amount. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980513.0145 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-13 08:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwait Cuts Spending When Oil Prices Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, May 13 (Xinhua) -- Kuwait, a leading oil producer,
will cut its expenditure to keep budget deficit from running out
of control under the impact of the plunge of world oil prices.
</P>
<P>
The Kuwaiti government and parliament reached an agreement on
the expenditure cut following an eight-hour marathon parliamentary
debate Tuesday night
</P>
<P>
Speaking after the closed-door session to discuss the
country's economy, Kuwaiti Finance Minister Sheikh Ali Salem
Al-Ali Al-Sabah said most members of the parliament and the
government turned down the idea of imposing increased charges on
public services during the 1998-99 fiscal year starting July 1,
and chose to axe expenditure.
</P>
<P>
The government will submit a detailed report to the parliament
in one month including its proposals on restructuring the economy
as a whole, he said, whose remarks were carried on all major
newspapers Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Economic analysts have said the impact of the low oil prices
since the start of this year on Kuwait's forthcoming budget will
be severe.
</P>
<P>
The Kuwaiti government late last month projected a 1.73 billion
Kuwaiti Dinars (5.7 billion U.S. dollars) deficit for the 1998-99
fiscal year for the oil-depending Gulf state which exports 3.5
percent of the world oil demand.
</P>
<P>
In mid-April, the 1998-99 budget, which is based on an oil
price of 12 dollars a barrel, was approved. It forecasts a deficit
of 5.6 billion dollars, the highest deficit since the Gulf War in
1991 and 41 percent higher than 1997-98 budgeted deficit.
</P>
<P>
Oil Minister Sheikh Saud Nasser Al-Sabah warned that Kuwait
could face an "economic catastrophe" if Kuwaiti crudes remained at
10.5 dollars a barrel.
</P>
<P>
The government and parliament also agreed last night to entrust
parliament's Finance and Economic Committee with reviewing budget
projections for the fiscal year in a bid to cut spending.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the finance minister also briefed the parliament
about the condition of the country's reserves and Future
Generations Fund.
</P>
<P>
According to independent sources, Kuwaiti state reserves are
at around 19.14 billion dollars and the Future Generation Fund at
39.6 billion dollars. Returns of investments abroad climbed to 4
billion dollars in 1997 from 2.5 billion dollars in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The parliament held the first secret session on May 2 to
discuss the financial situation. After the meeting, Kuwaiti
Deputy Prime Minister and Minister of State for Cabinet Affairs
Nasser Abdullah Al-Roudhan said the government wanted to
"diversify revenue (sources), reduce public expenditures and
improve the management of public funds in response to fall in oil
prices." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
