<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malawian Education System in Shambles: Paper </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, May 13 (Xinhua) -- Malawi's education system is in
shambles, rocked by massive examination failures, widespread
cheating, selling of examination forms, drug abuse and student
indiscipline, Zambia Daily Mail reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
According to government statistics, the 1996/97 school year
produced the worst recorded results ever. Out of 28,328
candidates who sat for university entry Malawi school leaving
certificate examinations (MSCE), 20,000 failed.
</P>
<P>
At least 6,000 of these candidates were disqualified for
cheating.
</P>
<P>
The Malawi National Examinations Board (MANEB) says there was
cheating in most examination centers. Candidates brought
reference materials to examination rooms, forcing the ministry
of education to nullify results in 24 schools before marking
started.
</P>
<P>
MANEB Executive Secretary Catherine Chimwenje says that
candidates were able to get hold of examination papers before the
examinations were held, but denies to say who should be
responsible for leaking them.
</P>
<P>
Many young people are abusing drugs and alcohol, and more are
experimenting with sex, says the ministry of social services.
</P>
<P>
Some young people, saying they are free to do as they please,
defy established authority. Pupils who are supposed to be in
school can be found in night clubs.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Education Brown Mpinganjira says the government
would like parents to become involved in the moulding of
children's characters. "We want teachers to take care of these
pupils and parents the behavior," he says.
</P>
<P>
Fed up with indiscipline, unwarranted dismissals and poor
examination results, guardians with government's blessing, have
formed the Malawi Parents Union (MPU) which will work closely
with schools.
</P>
<P>
"Parents and guardians should equally share the blame for
ignoring and neglecting their role to teach children good
manners," says MPU's coordinator James Chapna. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
