<HEADLINE> Thai Radanasin Bank Looks Foreign Partner </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, May 13 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's state-owned Radanasin
bank will increase its capital by 8 billion baht (2.1 billion U.S.
dollars) through selling shares to a strategic foreign partner,
according to a report Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Four billion baht will be raised through the sale of common
shares, with the other 4 billion baht raised from the sale of
convertible debentures.
</P>
<P>
The bank's current registered capital of 4 billion baht is
owned by the finance ministry. The bank was established earlier
this year to bid for assets from the 56 finance companies ordered
closed in December.
</P>
<P>
Vichit Suraphongchai, the bank's chairman, was quoted as saying
that the increase capital would allow the bank more leeway to bid.
</P>
<P>
The new strategic partner could end up with a majority
shareholding when debentures were converted in the future.
</P>
<P>
The new partner could be announced by late June. 
</P>
