<HEADLINE> Weed Threatens to Choke Kariba Lake in Zambia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, May 13 (Xinhua) -- Tourism operators in Siavonga along
Kariba lake in Zambia have urged the government to help them get
rid of the hyacinth, which is threatening to choke Kariba harbor
and distort its beauty and marine life.
</P>
<P>
The weed drifts daily in chunks as long as 50 meters from the
Zimbabwean side of the Kariba dam, Zambia Daily Mail reported
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The national newspaper quoted Manchinchi Bay Manager Jeremy
Lousada as saying that they are forced to spend hundreds of
thousands of Kwacha every month to keep the harbor clear and
attractive.
</P>
<P>
"We need a lasting solution because the weed drifts in
everyday. It is expensive to hire workers. The government should
help us keep tourism in Siavonga on its feet," he said.
</P>
<P>
The weed depletes oxygen for marine life and use of herbicides
though effective, could be fatal for aqua life forms.
</P>
<P>
Manchinchi bay spends about 200,000 Kwacha (about 100 U.S.
Dollars) per month to keep the harbor from being choked by the
weed.
</P>
<P>
Workers removing the weed at the bay complained that the work
is strenuous. They also fear that crocodiles are now getting
nearer to the harbor to prey on them as they clear the weed.
</P>
<P>
Lousada has commended Siavonga local authority for agreeing to
crop the crocodiles. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
