<HEADLINE> Mandela to Visit Remanded Kaunda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, May 13 (Xinhua) -- South African President Nelson
Mandela will visit remanded former Zambian President Kenneth
Kaunda next week, Zambia's Post newspaper reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The leading independent newspaper quoted a source from the
Zambian ministry of foreign affairs as saying in Lusaka Tuesday
that the Zambian government has been seeking to turn Mandela's
visit into a "state" one.
</P>
<P>
"But the Zambian government want him to come on a one-day
state visit," said the source, adding that "there are still
diplomatic discussions going on to see how this can be worked
out."
</P>
<P>
However, the source said it seems that the Zambian government
will succeed in turning what appears to be Mandela's "private"
visit to Kaunda into a "state" one. And it will be very
difficult for Mandela to completely turn down the Zambian
government's request.
</P>
<P>
In an interview Tuesday here with The Post, Walter Thabethe,
South African High Commissioner to Zambia, confirmed that Mandela
will be visiting Zambia sometime next week.
</P>
<P>
He said that Mandela is "definitely" coming to Zambia next
week, but the date is unknown.
</P>
<P>
Mandela, an old friend of Kaunda, is one of the southern
African presidents who called for the release of Kaunda, leader
of Zambia's largest opposition party -- the United National
Independence Party (UNIP).
</P>
<P>
Kaunda, 74, who led Zambia to independence from Britain in
1964 and ruled the country for 27 years, was arrested last
December in connection with the foiled military coup on October
28, 1997 on grounds that he had conspired with others to
overthrow the elected government.
</P>
<P>
On February 12, Kaunda was formally charged with misprision of
treason. 
</P>
</TEXT>
