<HEADLINE> Museveni Remains Tough on LRA Rebels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, May 13 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni
has said the government will maintain its hard-line policy of
fighting fire with fire when dealing with the rebels of the
Lord's Resistance Army (LRA).
</P>
<P>
The president Tuesday told the faithful in the northern
rebel-infested district of Gulu that both military and peaceful
means would be explored to end the 12-year-old northern
rebellion, local press reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
President Museveni said: "We shall pursue both peace and
pressure on the bad people and have that combination: peace and
hash ways. Everybody can struggle."
</P>
<P>
"Our Ugandan experience over the years is that bad people
cannot voluntarily give up their bad ways unless put under
pressure," he noted.
</P>
<P>
The LRA is a rebel group operating in the northern districts
of Kitgum and Gulu. It had 2,000 fighters in previous years and
only hundreds of remnants are left in its ranks now. The rebels
abducted local residents and looted their properties, posing a
major threat to the security in northern Uganda. 
</P>
</TEXT>
