<HEADLINE> China's Trade With Asia This Year To Match Last Year's Level </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 13 (Xinhua) -- A senior government official says
that China's trade with Japan, the Republic of Korea (ROK), and
ASEAN nations this year is expected to be worth at least 109.8
billion US dollars, matching last year's figure, although
first-quarter statistics show some problems in that trade.
</P>
<P>
The director of the Chinese Ministry of Foreign Trade and
Economic Cooperation's Asian Affairs Department, Hu Guocai,
attributes these to Japan's sluggish economic situation and the
impact of the Asian financial crisis on the ROK and ASEAN nations.
</P>
<P>
But, he says, the most difficult period has passed and the
prospects are still bright. He expects exports to these countries
this year to drop and imports from them to rise by a large margin,
meaning that total trade this year will be no less than for last
year.
</P>
<P>
He says that Japan is China's biggest trade partner and the ROK
is fourth, while Singapore, Indonesia, Malaysia and Thailand are
among China's top 20. Export to Japan, the ROK, and nine ASEAN
nations in the first quarter were down and exports to the ROK down
by as much as 22 percent.
</P>
<P>
China is concerned about these countries and has tried to
assist them, he says, and the government will encourage more
flexible means of trade between enterprises to expand bilateral
trade.
</P>
<P>
China's total trade with Japan, the ROK and the nine ASEAN
nations in the first quarter was worth 22 billion US dollars, up
6.9 percent from the same period of last year. Exports to these
countries were worth 10.2 billion US dollars, a decrease of 6.4
percent, and imports from them were worth 11.9 billion US dollars,
an increase of 5.5 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
