<DOCNO> XIE19980513.0159 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Academics Say Laws Are Needed to Protect Rare Fossils </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 13 (Xinhua) -- A group of 74 academics from the
Chinese Academy of Sciences have appealed to government
departments to provide greater legal protection of fossils here to
prevent improper excavations.
</P>
<P>
China boasts a large number of fossils, many of which are rare
specimens that could help the study of the evolution of the earth
and living things, said Yang Zunyi, a member of the group.
</P>
<P>
He acknowledged that there are many problems in the study of
fossils in China that have had a bad effect on the search for and
protection and study of rare fossils.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of fossilized dinosaur eggs found in Xixia in Henan
Province have been smuggled abroad, Yang said, and one exhibition,
sponsored by the Cambridge University museum, had more than 20
fossilized dinosaur eggs on display, which had been taken from
China. One, which contained an embryo, was the most perfect
example of its kind in the world. There is nothing similar in
China.
</P>
<P>
More than 100 rare bird fossils from the Mesozoic period, which
were unearthed in north east China's Liaoning Province, have
appeared in markets overseas and this situation needs to be
addressed, Yang noted.
</P>
<P>
He and other CAS academics have suggested that the Chinese
National People's Congress (NPC) improve the law on rare fossils
and designate certain departments and research institutes to
handle digging permits for rare fossils.
</P>
<P>
They also suggest that the Ministry of Science and Technology
set up a committee for the protection of rare fossils to be
responsible for planning and coordinating fossil searches by
various organizations.
</P>
<P>
In this way, China can improve researches on fossils and
improve its status internationally, the academic said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980513.0160 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya to Improve Hygienic Conditions in Fish </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, May 13 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan government has stepped
up its efforts to improve hygienic conditions in fishing
processing firms and the beaches in compliance with the European
Union (EU) requirements.
</P>
<P>
Major campaigns had been launched along the beaches of Lake
Victoria to improve handling of fish, the East African Standard
Wednesday quoted George Otieno, Nyanza Provincial Public Health
Officer, as saying.
</P>
<P>
Fishermen cooperative societies have agreed to build enough
latrines at the beaches to meet one of the EU conditions,
according to the health officer.
</P>
<P>
He noted that other conditions like having piped water at the
beaches and required temperature in processing plants were being
addressed.
</P>
<P>
A task force comprising fishermen, fishery and public health
officials, and fish processors was set up to oversee the
campaigns, he said, adding that the task force would soon visit
fish processing plants to assess their hygienic conditions.
</P>
<P>
EU imposed a ban on import of fresh fish from Mozambique,
Tanzania, Uganda and Kenya early this year on the pretext of
their failure to meet health standards set by the EU.
</P>
<P>
The EU requires Kenyan fish exporters and processors to
harmonize fish inspection standards by June this year, which
covers capture, killing, handling and packaging.
</P>
<P>
All fish products must be analyzed and examined by an
accredited laboratory prior to export to the EU market, according
to EU requirements. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
