<HEADLINE> U.S. Governor Calls for National Conference on Tobacco </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, May 12 (Xinhua) -- Jim Gilmore, governor of the
state of Virginia, called Tuesday for a national conference next
month on a proposed tobacco legislation in U.S. Congress.
</P>
<P>
The legislation proposed by Sen. John McCain, a Republican
representing the state of Arizona, would put thousands of people
out of work, Gilmore was quoted as saying by reports reaching here.
</P>
<P>
Under the bill, a 516-billion-dollar settlement would replace
the 368-billion-dollar deal reached last June to settle 40 state
lawsuits seeking coverage of tobacco-related health care costs.
</P>
<P>
"We need to join together to send a clear message to Congress
that we are united in opposition to these measures," Gilmore said
in a letter to the state chapter of America's largest union group.
</P>
<P>
He also asked labor leaders nationwide to help organize the
June meeting, to be focused on preventing underage smoking and
protecting families whose livelihood depends on tobacco.
</P>
<P>
Tobacco is Virginia's leading cash crop and some 120,000
Virginian workers depend on tobacco for a living. 
</P>
</TEXT>
