<HEADLINE> PNA Asks Israelis to Stay out During Mass March </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, May 13 (Xinhua) -- The Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) has asked Israelis to keep away from its
territories starting Wednesday, to prevent possible trouble during
or before a massive march there on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
PNA officials have told their Israeli counterparts not to
allow Israelis, even peace groups, to enter PNA territories,
warning of possible attack by radical Palestinians on them, a
senior PNA official told Xinhua on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The PNA will organize a massive march on Thursday in Gaza
Strip and the West Bank to mark the 50th anniversary of "Nakba"
(catastrophe), or the 50th anniversary of the state of Israel, on
the secular calendar.
</P>
<P>
The march, which is expected to attract about 1 million people,
comes as PNA officials and legislators are expressing concern that
the breakdown of the Palestinian-Israeli peace talks will result
in violence in the territories.
</P>
<P>
The marchers will be well-organized, but the PNA can not rule
out the possibility that the demonstrations could turn into
violent anti-Israeli protests, said the official who spoke on
condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
The PNA's request also comes as Israeli defense officials
predict that the massive march would result in violent Palestinian
clashes with the Israeli Defense Forces if the demonstrations run
out of control.
</P>
<P>
Palestinians regarded the founding of the state of Israel 50
years ago was a disaster for them, because millions of
Palestinians were forced to leave their homeland and turned into
refugees. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
