<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Athletes Should Have More Competitions, Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, Southwest China, May 13 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese
athletics chief said here on Thursday that Chinese athletes should
cut their training time short to expose themselves more in
international competitions.
</P>
<P>
Lou Dapeng, president of the Chinese Athletics Association and
executive memter of the world athletics ruling body IAAF, said
that both athletes and coaches had to change their traditional
concept that hard training was sure to lead to better results in
competitions.
</P>
<P>
"Such concept is out of date. If you stay in a closed
environment, you won't gain battle experience no matter how hard
you are training," Lou told Xinhua after the eye-popping World
Fastest Woman 100m Race on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Li Xuemei, hailed as a tough challenge to American
world champion Marion Jones before the race, finished only fourth
with a modest 11.21 seconds, well out of her personal best of
10.79 set in the Chinese National Games last year.
</P>
<P>
Jones took an easy win before a partisan crowd of 20,000,
clocking a superb 10.71, her personal best and the world's best
since 1988.
</P>
<P>
Bahamas's Savatheda Fynes and Chandra Sturrup, third and fourth
finisher in the race, clocked their personal best time of 11.06
and 11.09 respectively.
</P>
<P>
"I had believed that I could run well before the race," Li
said. "But when I stepped onto the track and saw so many fans
cheering for me, I was really nervous."
</P>
<P>
Li's coach Zhang Rongwei had predicted the gap between Jones
and his protege would be within 0.05 seconds since Li posted 10.90
in her training Tuesday morning. The final results turned out a
heavy blow to the training-oriented coach.
</P>
<P>
"Training and competing are no longer two different things for
foreign athletes," Lou said. "Competing is part of training.
</P>
<P>
"World-class athletes usually take part in 20 competitions
every year while Chinese athletes always bury themselves in
training before big events."
</P>
<P>
Within 10 days prior to the Fastest Woman Race, sprinter-jumper
Jones had competed in two meets in Japan. She long-jumped 7.05
meters in her first meet and ran a fabulous 10.79 in her second
outing in the Osaka Grand Prix, while Li skipped several
competitions in Europe to prepare for a shot at the American.
</P>
<P>
Li admitted that lack of experience was the main reason for her
second waterloo defeat since last year's world championships.
</P>
<P>
In the Athens world championships, Li was ousted out of the 100
meters semi-finals after clocking 11.21 seconds.
</P>
<P>
"There is a gap between Jones and me, but not as big as shown
in Wednesday's race," said the 21-year-old Chinese sprint
queen.
</P>
<P>
"I can run sub-11 seconds," Li said. "I need more head-to-head
meetings with the world best sprinters to steel my nerves."
</P>
<P>
Zhang Rongwei said his student would stick at closed-door
training because "competition was by no means the key to good
performance."
</P>
<P>
"We prefer daily closed-door training, which remains the
foundation of good performance," Zhang said. "We will not blindly
copy foreign athletes' methods." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980513.0184 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-13 </DATE_TIME>
