<HEADLINE> Thai Radanasin Bank Looks to Foreign Partner </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, May 13 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's state-owned Radanasin
Bank will increase its capital by eight billion baht (2.1 billion
U.S. dollars) through selling shares to a strategic foreign
partner, according to a report here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Four billion baht will be raised through the sale of common
shares, with the other four billion baht raised from the sale of
convertible debentures.
</P>
<P>
The bank's current registered capital of four billion baht is
owned by the Finance Ministry. The bank was established earlier
this year to bid for assets from the 56 finance companies ordered
closed last December.
</P>
<P>
Vichit Suraphongchai, the bank's chairman, was quoted as saying
that the increased capital would allow the bank more leeway to
bid.
</P>
<P>
The new strategic partner could end up with a majority share
holding when debentures were converted in the future.
</P>
<P>
The new partner could be announced by late June. 
</P>
