<HEADLINE> Baltic Nations Hold Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, May 12 (Xinhua) -- The presidents of Lithuania, Latvia
and Estonia have condemned Russia for trying to pressure Latvia in
its treatment of ethnic Russians.
</P>
<P>
But at a summit meeting of the three Baltic states on Tuesday
in the Latvian capital Riga, they unanimously stressed that they
were keen to maintain good relations with all their neighbors,
including Russia.
</P>
<P>
Gontis Vlmanis, Latvia's president, his Lithuanian and Estonian
counterparts Valdas Adamkus and Lennart Meri also met to discuss
regional affairs, economic cooperation and the implementation of
the U.S.-Baltic Partnership Charter.
</P>
<P>
The three presidents said cooperation among the three Baltic
states would not be affected by the political and economic
pressure Russia brought to bear on Latvia.
</P>
<P>
Relations with Russia have grown tense since the Baltic nations
signed the partnership charter with the United States on January
16, sparking Russian fears of the eastward expansion of the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization.
</P>
<P>
Russian-Latvian ties worsened in early March, when ethnic
Russians in Latvia protesting against rising tariffs were beaten
by Latvian police, causing anger in Russia.
</P>
<P>
In response to Russian threats, the Latvian Foreign Ministry
said on March 9, "Attempts to influence Latvia by economic
sanctions will draw a negative response from the European Union
countries and other partner states." 
</P>
</TEXT>
