<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980513.0193 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Anniversary Of Certain Victory Operation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, May 13 (Xinhua) -- One year ago to this day, Sri
Lankan government forces launched a major offensive to clear a
main supply route of 75 kilometers through Tamil rebels-held
territory in the north of the country.
</P>
<P>
A total of 20,000 troops were mobilized for the operation
code-named Jaya Sikuru (Certain Victory). But to date, despite the
superiority of strength, equipment and air and naval resources,
the government troops have been able to advance only 45
kilometers, leaving a further 30 kilometers to be cleared.
</P>
<P>
During the year-long operation, both sides suffered heavy
casualties. At least 2,500 rebels have been killed and over 7,500
others injured while about 1,400 government troops died in action
with over 5,500 wounded, according to reports in the newspaper
Sunday Times.
</P>
<P>
Additionally military hardware including artillery guns,
mortars, armed vehicles and tanks worth millions of U.S. dollars
have been lost or damaged.
</P>
<P>
In terms of expenditure, an estimated 9 million U.S. dollars,
excluding the cost of military hardware, has been spent on the
operation.
</P>
<P>
The slow progress of the operation and the heavy resistance
encountered by the government forces have raised the question
whether the strength, capability and strategies of the enemy had
been under- estimated when the operation was launched, the reports
said.
</P>
<P>
The government has also now come to realize that the army is
short of manpower. Army Commander Lt. Gen. Rohan Daluwatte has
admitted that the army's advance has been hampered by the lack of
manpower.
</P>
<P>
The manpower shortage has been aggravated by the desertion of
an estimated 15,000 soldiers. The amnesties offered to deserters
on a number of occasions and a high geared recruiting drive
indicate the real predicament of the army with regard to manpower.
The suggestion of resorting to conscription should manpower levels
not be filled through normal recruitment underscores the problem
the government is facing,.
</P>
<P>
Observers here said that the operation has neither been a
success nor a failure so far in the theater. But given the inputs
that have gone into the operation at the expense of security in
other vulnerable areas, the validity of a main supply route
strategy is arguable.
</P>
<P>
Operation Jaya Sikuru should be assessed in the light of its
failures, successes and overall objectivity. The observers said it
appears that the operation planners had either underestimated the
enemy and overestimated their own capability or subordinated it to
a political agenda disregarding a rational appreciation.
</P>
<P>
Whatever the contributory factors, it is clear that there has
been a mismatch between the military and political plans and the
assessment of capabilities, logistics and aims, they said.
</P>
<P>
These shortcomings have at the end of one year of fighting
every inch of the way been able only to develop a stalemate
situation. The Tamil rebels may be weaker than what it was when
the operation began but that has not made an appreciable dent to
their military ambitions.
</P>
<P>
The rebels were not quiet during the year. In addition to
holding the forces back from over-running their stronghold and
making them pay heavily for every inch won, they attacked other
urban targets.
</P>
<P>
They bombed the Galadhari Hotel in Colombo last October, the
Dalada Maligawa (Temple of the Tooth) in Kandy sacred to Buddhists
and the Maradana intersection in the heart of Colombo city at
lunch time peak hour in February and March this year respectively.
They further persisted in their attacks on military establishments
in the east and other parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
However, military sources said the Jaya Sikuru operation will
go on to next year unless another strategy is evolved.
</P>
<P>
As commander-in-chief, President Chandrika Kumaratunga, to her
credit. has spared on costs once she made her decision to combat
the Tamil rebels. This was after they reneged on their undertaking
during the last 1994 peace talks.
</P>
<P>
The Tamil rebels have been fighting a 15-year-old war against
the Sri Lankan government for a separate Tamil state in the north
and east of the country. Over 55,000 people have reportedly been
killed in the war. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980513.0194 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brazilian President Meets Senior Chinese Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRASILIA, May 12 (Xinhua) -- President Fernando Henrique
Cardoso, in a meeting with a senior Chinese official here Tuesday,
said Brazil and China should work together to further develop
friendly relations.
</P>
<P>
In the meeting with Tian Jiyun, vice chairman of the Standing
Committee of the National People's Congress (NPC) of China,
Cardoso said that his country attaches great importance to
developments in China, particularly the strengthening of the role
of the NPC in the political life of China.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on the same occasion, Tian said that both Brazil and
China are developing nations and have the potential to develop
good relationships.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government and the NPC look forward to building a
lasting and stable relationship with the Brazilian government and
people, Tian said.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders also exchanged views on trade, economic and
technological cooperation as well as strengthening cooperation in
international affairs.
</P>
<P>
Tian also met with Brazilian Senate President Antonio Carlos de
Magalhaes and President of the Chamber of Deputies Michael Temer
earlier Tuesday. During these meetings, the two sides agreed that
an exchange of visits in the two legislatures will help deepen
mutual understanding and promote friendship between the two
peoples.
</P>
<P>
Tian arrived in Sao Paulo last Friday to start a five-day visit
to Brazil. He is scheduled to leave for Chile on Wednesday and
will eventually continue on to Peru. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
