<HEADLINE> Xinhua World Economic News Summary at 0500 GMT, May 13 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA -- Indonesia needs to import a significant amount of
rice to meet this year's demand for the commodity, a government
official said.
</P>
<P>
Head of the National Logistics Agency Beddu Amang said here
Tuesday that it will be difficult for Indonesia to regain
self-sufficiency in rice in the near future, Antara News Agency
reported Wednesday. (Indonesia-Rice)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BEIJING -- Zhongguancun, Beijing's computer trading hub, has
attracted a number of international computer name brands for its
mature marketing system as well as rich resources of research and
marketing personnel.
</P>
<P>
The likes of Microsoft, IBM, Intel and Mitsubishi have
established their Asian Headquarters or research-and-development
centers in Zhongguancun, or cooperate with local businesses in
making information products. (China-Computer)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The U.S. Agriculture Department predicted here
Tuesday that the American farmers will harvest a winter wheat crop
down 9 percent from last year at 1.71 billion bushels.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the early predictions for this country's corn crop,
indicated farmers will have 9.64 billion bushels, which would be
the second-largest on record. Soybean production is tentatively
projected at 2.8 billion bushels, up 3 percent from last year's
record. (US-Agriculture-Prediction)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LONDON -- The UK's manufacturing output fell for the second
consecutive quarter, officially confirming that the sector is now
mired in recession.
</P>
<P>
Factory output fell by 0.1 percent in the first three months of
this year following a 0.5 percent drop in the previous quarter,
according to the latest official figures by the Office of National
Statistics. (UK-Economy)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ISLAMABAD -- Foreign investment in Pakistan, both direct and
portfolio, amounted to 639.9 million U.S. dollars in the first
three quarters of the 1997-98 fiscal year (July 1-June 30).
</P>
<P>
This shows a slight improvement in the private foreign
investment inflow, when compared with the investment in the
corresponding period of the previous fiscal
year. (Pakistan-Foreign Investment)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TOKYO -- Japan's domestic wholesale prices had dropped 2.3
percent in April from a year earlier, posting the biggest fall
since July 1987, the Bank of Japan (BOJ) said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
In April, the domestic wholesale price index, which measures
inflation on the level of corporate transactions and is considered
to foreshadow trends in consumer prices, stood at 97.6 against the
1995 base of 100. (Japan-Wholesale Prices)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
SINGAPORE -- The Monetary Authority of Singapore (MAS) is
committed to opening up the country's financial sector to more
competition, Deputy Prime Minister Lee Hsien Loong, who is also
chairman of the MAS, said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The MAS will allow market participants more free play to
innovate and take risk, he said at the opening of a two-day
seminar jointly hosted by the World Bank's Economic Development
Institute and the MAS. (Singapore-Financial-Openness)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
CANBERRA -- Australian Treasurer Peter Costello predicted on
Tuesday that the current Asian financial and economic crisis would
have a significant impact on the Australian economy.
</P>
<P>
"The financial and economic crisis in Asia will have a
significant influence on the Australian economy in (the fiscal
year of) 1998-99," he told parliament when delivering his third
budget. (Australia-Economy-Asian Crisis)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BONN -- Germany's economic growth is set to pick up steam in
the next two years, but this will still be insufficient to stem
the country's record-high unemployment, six leading German
economic research institutes predicted Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"The general economic conditions as well as the overwhelmingly
positive estimates shared by enterprises all speak in favor of a
continuing and even a strengthening economic upswing," said a
joint spring economic report issued by the six institutes
comprising the government's Council of Economic
Advisors. (German-Economy) 
</P>
