<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. China Policy Defined in Terms of Objective: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 12 (Xinhua) -- The United States' China policy
should be defined in terms of its objective, strategy and tactic,
a senior U.S. official said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at American Enterprise Institute for Public Research,
Assistant Secretary of State for East Asia and Pacific Affairs
Stanley Roth said the reality was far broader than engagement.
</P>
<P>
"All too often, China policy is reduced to one simple
word, 'engagement,' or sometimes people are more generous; they
reduce it to two words, 'comprehensive engagement,' but the
reality ... is far more complex," he said.
</P>
<P>
Roth said the objective of U.S. China policy was to seek a
strong, stable, prosperous and open China, and its strategy is
integrating China into regional and global institutions.
Engagement is the tactic for achieving the goals, he added.
</P>
<P>
"This is the framework that we have in mind as we were moving
towards the last summit," he pointed out.
</P>
<P>
Chinese President Jiang Zemin visited the United States and
held a summit meeting with U.S. President Bill Clinton last
October, an event which was described by both sides as a
milestone in the bilateral relationship.
</P>
<P>
"I think one of the least noted accomplishments of the summit
was the fact that we agreed upon regular high-level engagement and
we took out the notion that engagement is now somehow a reward for
specific behavior patterns and instead substituted the notion that
engagement is something you do because these are two very
important players who for better or for worse have to deal with
each other and, preferably, get along with each other," Roth said.
</P>
<P>
After the summit, U.S.Secretary of Defense William Cohen and
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright visited China prior to the
next Sino-U.S. summit scheduled for late June. "This engagement
is really proceeding quite vigorously," Roth said.
</P>
<P>
The meetings between high-ranking Chinese and U.S. officials
had focused on such important issues as human rights,
non-proliferation and economic links. Progress has been made on
these issues, Roth believed.
</P>
<P>
However, he stressed that "the biggest accomplishment was our
agreement, as noted in the joint statement, to move towards a
constructive strategic dialogue, or partnership."
</P>
<P>
He said he was surprised to hear some people interpret the
phrase of constructive strategic partnership as a military
alliance. "I think the easiest thing is to simply say: never
intended in that fashion. That's not China's concept of this, this
is, you know, not what we mean.
</P>
<P>
"What we're rather talking about is looking for a framework on
which we can, you know, come up with maximizing the number of
issues we can work on together," he said.
</P>
<P>
Roth believed that the better U.S.-China relationship had
helped to foster better cross-strait dialogue, and had immensely
strengthened U.S.-Taiwan relationship. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
