<HEADLINE> Khmer Rouge Radio off the Air </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, May 13 (Xinhua) -- The clandestine Khmer Rouge
radio went off the air on Wednesday morning amid speculation over
its whereabouts.
</P>
<P>
General Chea Sarun, head of the Operations Bureau of the
General Staff, told reporters that there were unconfirmed reports
that the radio was destroyed by the guerrillas who betrayed Khmer
Rouge's military chief Ta Mok, or it had technical problems.
</P>
<P>
According to Meas Sophea, deputy chief of general staff of the
Royal Army of Cambodia, the radio was probably moved west to a
place known as "Ta Tum camp" from its original base in Anlong Veng
along the Cambodia-Thai border.
</P>
<P>
Meas Sophea, who commanded government troops against the Khmer
Rouge guerrillas, said the automobile-mounted radio always
retreated when government soldiers approached.
</P>
<P>
The mobile radio was claimed to be captured by government
troops on Monday's attacks, but it continued to broadcast Tuesday,
with the announcers alleging that 16 government soldiers were
killed by land mines during the fighting on Saturday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
