<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Dhaka Silent Over India's Nuclear Tests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, May 13 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladeshi government has
remained silent since its close neighbor India announced that it
had conducted three underground nuclear tests Monday, its first in
24 years.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh continued to remain committed to world peace and
stability, particularly in South Asia, State Minister for Foreign
Affairs Abul Hasan Chowdhury said Tuesday, shunning to comment on
the blasts, press reports said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope that all the countries of the region
would move away from arms race to utilize resources "for the
welfare of mankind as well as poverty alleviation and eradication
of illiteracy."
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh signed the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty in October
1996, he said.
</P>
<P>
"We have no comment now and we are observing the developments",
a Foreign Ministry spokesman said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Bangladeshi scientists and experts, however, have expressed
their concern over India's nuclear tests which they said would
trigger a fresh arms race in South Asia.
</P>
<P>
Professor B.K. Jahangir, a political scientist and vice
chancellor of National University on the outskirts of Dhaka, said
that the latest provocation to arms race in the region following
India's first nuclear test conducted in 1974 was "very
unfortunate" for a region troubled by problems like poverty,
illiteracy and very large but unskilled population.
</P>
<P>
Such developments, he said, were bound to create serious
imbalance of power particularly when spending on deadly weapons
was getting priority by neglecting problems like poverty,
illiteracy and lack of skill of the unfortunate population.
</P>
<P>
He said that the arms race to be triggered by the multiple
blasts conducted in a single day by India would force the two big
countries of South Asia to go on a spending spree on armaments
spoiling much of their resources.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Talukdar Moniuruzzaman, a renowned political scientist,
said he could not understand how India could gain out of its
latest tests.
</P>
<P>
The blasts conducted by India Monday were unlikely to change
the existing status quo of arms between the two arch rival nations
-- India and Pakistan -- of the region, he said.
</P>
<P>
Professor M. Shahiduzzaman of the International Relations
Department of Dhaka University said the nuclear explosions
conducted by India would heighten instability in the subcontinent.
</P>
<P>
He said India already demonstrated by its latest actions that
it possessed much more developed nuclear capability than Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
India's new government, after coming to power last month, made
its option to introduce nuclear weapons, a key plank of its
platform in the elections.
</P>
<P>
India has refused to sign the Nuclear Non-proliferation Treaty
and the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty, claiming the two treaties
to be discriminatory. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
