<HEADLINE> Unofficial Results: Estrada Leads in Presidential Race </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, May 13 (Xinhua) -- As vote counting has entered its
third day Wednesday, unofficial partial results show Vice
President Joseph Estrada and Senator Gloria Macapagal-Arroyo are
leading in the Philippines' presidential and vice presidential
elections.
</P>
<P>
The official counting, which began immediately after the polls
closed Monday, has not reached at the provincial level and the
official partial results still cannot tell who are really leading
in the country's national and local elections.
</P>
<P>
But the latest unofficial partial results provided by the
National Citizens Movement for Free Elections (Namfrel) as of
01:39 Wednesday (17:39 GMT Tuesday), show Vice President Joseph
Estrada, standard bearer of the opposition Laban ng Makabayang
Masang Pilipino (Fight of Patriotic Filipinos Masses), is leading
with 386,123 votes in the presidential race.
</P>
<P>
Senator Macapagal-Arroyo, candidate of the ruling Lakas-NUCD
(National Union of Christian Democrats), is leading with 421,884
votes in the vice presidential election.
</P>
<P>
Vice President Estrada was followed by Senator Raul Roco of
Aksyon Demokratiko (Democratic Action) with 143,601 votes. Speaker
Jose de Venecia of the ruling Lakas-NUCD party trailed third with
119,504 votes, while former Manila mayor Alfredo Lim of the
Liberal Party was in the fourth place with 113,865 votes.
</P>
<P>
Namfrel is the sole non-government organization authorized by
the Commission on Elections to conduct unofficial quick count
operations.
</P>
<P>
The official vote counting has been proceeding very slowly.
After the counting at the precinct level, election inspectors will
turn over the election returns to the municipal or city level.
</P>
<P>
The total election returns will be recorded and tabulated and
then given to the provincial level.
</P>
<P>
The forms will then be forwarded to the House of
Representatives for the counting for the presidential and vice
presidential positions, while the Commission on Elections will
count the votes for the congressional posts.
</P>
<P>
The process is expected to take four weeks. But the Namfrel can
release the unofficial final results within 10 days.
</P>
<P>
According to the Commission on Elections, about 80 percent of
the 34 million voters turned out Monday to cast ballots to choose
a president, a vice president, 12 out of 24 senators, 260 members
of the House of Representatives and more than 17,000 local
officials and councilors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980513.0204 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> North China City Signs Friendship Agreement with German City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, May 13 (Xinhua) -- North China's Taiyuan, capital of
Shanxi Province, will formally establish a friendly relationship
with the German city of Chemnitz later this year as a result of a
six-day visit by a delegation from Chemnitz which ended Monday.
</P>
<P>
According to initial agreements reached by the two sides,
mutual visits focusing on infrastructure and high-tech projects
will be arranged each year. Non-governmental exchanges between the
two cities will also be enhanced.
</P>
<P>
"Taiyuan is a fast-growing city with a huge potential; I
believe that our cooperation will have bright prospects," said
Peter Seifert, mayor of Chemnitz.
</P>
<P>
According to Taiyuan Mayor Cao Zhonghou, a friendly
relationship with Chemnitz will introduce more sophisticated
technologies and more funds for its own development, and will
bring a good opportunity for his city to accelerate its opening-up.
</P>
<P>
The delegation from the German city of Chemnitz visited Taiyuan
from May 6 to 11. 
</P>
</TEXT>
