<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zhongguancun Embraces International Name Brands </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 13 (Xinhua) -- Zhongguancun, Beijing's computer
trading hub, has attracted a number of international computer name
brands for its mature marketing system as well as rich resources
of research and marketing personnel.
</P>
<P>
The likes of Microsoft, IBM, Intel and Mitsubishi have
established their Asian Headquarters or research-and-development
centers in Zhongguancun, or cooperate with local businesses in
making information products.
</P>
<P>
There are 920 overseas-funded new-technology enterprises with
an investment of 960 million U.S. dollars registered in the
Haidian area around Zhongguancun, which is the city's education
and research center.
</P>
<P>
Many overseas managers said that Zhongguancun provides the best
market conditions and personnel, which means higher returns for
businesses here than elsewhere since high-tech tends to be a
costly and risky business.
</P>
<P>
International cooperation between businesses, universities and
research bodies from both home and abroad have permeated the
research, manufacturing, marketing and after-sale service of all
the leading businesses in Zhongguancun.
</P>
<P>
Many joint ventures make products developed from local
research. A survey of 390 joint ventures in the area shows that
the Chinese partner uses technology as investment shares in 107 of
them, while the overseas partner does the same in 33.
</P>
<P>
Economic globalization is giving Zhongguancun businesses easier
access to international funding, technology, personnel, and
markets, said Shao Xinping, an official with the administration
committee of the Haidian area.
</P>
<P>
However, facing competition from foreign consortia, the
fledgling Chinese electronics industry must work together on the
global scene, he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980513.0207 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-13 </DATE_TIME>
