<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0100 GMT, May 13 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO -- At least 19 people were injured Tuesday evening after
a fire broke out in one of the engines of a United Airlines jumbo
jet at Tokyo's Narita International Airport.
</P>
<P>
A Kyodo News report said the injured were among the 365
passengers and 20 crew members on UA Flight 801 bound for Hong
Kong, the report said. (Japan-Plane-Fire)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BUCHAREST -- Romanian armed forces will stage a number of joint
war exercises in Romania with forces from other countries.
</P>
<P>
Approval came at a joint conference on Tuesday between
Romania's two parliaments, a Romanian News Agency report said.
</P>
<P>
In the coming four months, forces from Romania, France and the
United States will exercise in Romanian territory. Exercises
include one scheduled from June 5 to 9. (Romania-War Exercises)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The Pentagon's fifth missile defense system
failed to intercept a target on Tuesday, the Defense Department
said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The test on the Theater High-Altitude Area Defense, or THAAD
system, was done at White Sands Missile Range, New Mexico. The
missile, built by Lockhead Martin Corp., lost control shortly
after launch, the statement said. It appeared to be caused by a
booster rocket problem. (US-Anti-Missile-Test)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
GENEVA -- Over 18,000 whales have been killed since 1985
despite the international efforts to conserve them, according to a
new report released Tuesday by World Wide Fund for Nature (WWF).
</P>
<P>
The report, Great Whales in the Wild, is in preparation for
this year's meeting of the International Whaling Commission (IWC)
to be held in Oman on May 16-20. (WWF-Whaling)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
NEW DELHI -- Charge D'affaires Ad Interim of the Chinese
Embassy in India Lin Shanglin rejected here Tuesday what he called
the recent slanderous rumors of a "China Threat" by some
Indians. He reiterated China's independent foreign policy of peace.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a press conference at the embassy, Lin said China is
now fully dedicated to its modernization drive as well as reforms
and opening up. This needed a long-term peaceful international
environment, particularly a good surrounding
environment. (China-Indian-Refutation)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- Secretary of State Madeleine Albright said
Tuesday that she would re-issue invitations to the Israeli and
Palestinian leaders to Washington for a summit if she could reach
agreement with Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu on
Wednesday's talks.
</P>
<P>
But she insisted a U.S. proposal on Israel's pullback from 13
percent of the West Bank would not be watered down for that
purpose. (US-Israel-Albright)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BERLIN -- U.S. President Bill Clinton will start a European
trip with a visit to Germany Wednesday and Thursday, where he will
highlight new prospects for transatlantic relations between the
United States and Europe, U.S. Ambassador to Germany John Kornblum
said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Clinton will attend ceremonies Thursday at the Tempelhof
Airport of Berlin marking the 50th anniversary of the Berlin
airlift, an operation staged by the Western allies in 1948-49 to
bring supplies to the then West Berlin during a blockade by Soviet
troops. (Germany-US-Visit)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The United Arab Emirates will buy up to 80
U.S.-made F-16 fighter jets in a deal worth about 6 billion
dollars, the UAE's crown prince and U.S. Vice President Al Gore
said in a statement after White House talks Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
After the talks with UAE Crown Prince Sheik Khalifa bin Zayed
Al Nahyan, Gore said the United States was setting the seal on a
strategic partnership. (US-UAE-Warplanes) 
</P>
