<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada Recalls High Commissioner to India </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, May 12 (Xinhua) -- Canada said Tuesday that it is
recalling its high commissioner in New Delhi to protest India's
nuclear weapons test explosions.
</P>
<P>
"We are recalling our High Commissioner to India as a first
concrete step in signaling our disapproval to the Indian
government," Foreign Affairs Minister Lloyd Axworthy said in a
statement released here.
</P>
<P>
Canadian High Commissioner Peter Walker will be returning to
Canada this week for an indeterminate period of time, according to
the statement.
</P>
<P>
The Canadian government will "determine the best course of
action in response to India's clear breach of international
security," the minister noted.
</P>
<P>
Canada strongly deplored the three nuclear weapons test
explosions carried out India early Monday, and announced by Indian
Prime Minister Vajpayee later on.
</P>
<P>
"We are deeply concerned and very disappointed with India's
decision to carry out these nuclear tests," Axworthy said shortly
after India announced the explosions.
</P>
<P>
"This incident is contrary to the international norms
established by the Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty (NPT) and the
Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty (CTBT)," the minister said.
</P>
<P>
"These tests could have grave implications for global
non-proliferation and disarmament, as well as for regional
security," he warned.
</P>
<P>
Also Tuesday, Canada's Secretary of State for Asia-Pacific
affairs Raymond Chan reiterated that Canada strongly urges India
to sign on to the NPT and CTBT.
</P>
<P>
"We also urge countries in the region to show restraint in
their reaction to yesterday's incident," Chan added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
