<DOCNO> XIE19980513.0217 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> House Toughens Penalties for Evading Child Support </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 12 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. House of
Representatives voted Tuesday to raise the penalties for parents
who cross state lines to evade child support.
</P>
<P>
The legislation would make it a felony, with prison terms of up
to six months, for a parent to cross a state border to avoid child
support when the amount of money owed is 5,000 dollars or more and
is more than one year past due.
</P>
<P>
Parents owing 10,000 dollars or more or those fail to pay for
two years could face up to two years in prison. Parents could
also face fines and would be responsible for making restitution
for unpaid child support.
</P>
<P>
Current law makes it only a misdemeanor, with crimes, to cross
state lines to avoid payments.
</P>
<P>
The bill, which passed 402-16, was approved in almost identical
form by the Senate last November. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
