<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy Voices Disappointment with Indian Nuclear Tests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, May 12 (Xinhua) -- Italy's Foreign Ministry Tuesday
described India's unexpected nuclear tests as "deplorable" and
urged New Delhi to join a global ban on nuclear testing.
</P>
<P>
The ministry also expressed concern over Indian behavior that
contrasts with the international community's efforts to
consolidate disarmament and nuclear non-proliferation.
</P>
<P>
"The ministry hopes that despite this deplorable act, everyone
will show responsibility in supporting the international
community's determination to pursue the goals enshrined in the
Comprehensive Nuclear Test Ban Treaty," the ministry said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
"Italy invites the new government in New Delhi to review its
position and adhere to the Test Ban Treaty as soon as possible,"
it added.
</P>
<P>
It added that the Comprehensive Nuclear Test Ban Treaty had
been signed by 149 countries and was in the process of ratification.
</P>
<P>
Outside the Indian embassy in Rome, about 20 members of the
Italian Green party demonstrated Tuesday against the tests. They
also called on the Italian government to urge the European Union
to take strong action, at least on a par with the United States,
which is looking at sanctions.
</P>
<P>
India set off three nuclear devices on Monday and also tested a
short-range Trident missile, capable of hitting targets up to 350
kilometers away. The tests, the first since 1974, have sparked
worldwide protests.
</P>
<P>
Italy's Greenpeace group also issued a statement, saying: "To
prevent a possible arms race triggered by the Indian tests, the
international community should send a clear signal: nuclear tests
are unacceptable and intolerable."
</P>
<P>
It said that the U.S., France and Canada must be blamed for the
tests. "It is they who provide India with nuclear materials or
help it build nuclear facilities."
</P>
<P>
The statement revealed that India is capable of producing 75 to
200 kilograms of plutonium a year, five to ten times more than
needed to generate nuclear electricity.
</P>
<P>
New Delhi has signed neither the nuclear nonproliferation
treaty nor any test ban agreement, arguing that the treaties
discriminate against developing nations in favor of the wealthy
nuclear states. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
