<HEADLINE> Death Toll Climbs to 139 Following Mudslides in Italy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, May 12 (Xinhua) -- The death toll from Italy's mudslides
rose to 139 while 146 people are still listed as missing one week
after the disaster hit the southern Campania region.
</P>
<P>
Official reports Tuesday said 89 people were hospitalized and
1,034 left homeless after torrents of mud and debris rushed down
hills following days of heavy rains.
</P>
<P>
More than 4,000 rescue workers were still searching the five
disaster-stricken towns between Naples and Salerno for survivors.
</P>
<P>
In the worst hit city of Sarno, Mayor Massimo Siano said most
roads leading to the town have been cleared and work would begin
on the local cemetery where the slides toppled tombs and scattered
human remains.
</P>
<P>
"This is a sensitive problem because of hygienic
considerations," said Siano.
</P>
<P>
On the plight of the homeless, the mayor said the municipality
would use containers and campers only as a last resort because
housing was available in the surrounding communities, and there
were buildings constructed for victims of previous earthquakes
that were never used.
</P>
<P>
The catastrophe last week put Italy's environmental issues in
the spotlight as unregulated development, illegal construction and
deforestation were in part to blamed for the massive mudslides.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
