<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> First "Telephone Village" in Tibet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, May 13 (Xinhua) -- Goinbo, a 71-year-old Tibetan, was
very excited after telephoning his grandson who was studying in
east China's Fujian Province more than 3,000 km away.
</P>
<P>
"It used to take more than 20 days to receive a letter from my
grandson. Now we can telephone him and get his voice so clearly,
just like a face-to-face conversation," he said.
</P>
<P>
Goinbo lives in the Gonchum Village in Nyingchi Prefecture, 410
km east to Lhasa, capital of Tibet.
</P>
<P>
Since March, 12 households among the 14 ones in the village
have had telephones with direct distance dialing (DDD) function,
through which villagers can reach other parts of the
country. Gonchum, thus, became the first "telephone village" in
Tibet.
</P>
<P>
With the development of the infrastructure in Nyingchi in
recent years, residents in the nearby Gonchum Village began doing
businesses of forestry product processing and transportation. Last
year, their average income per capita surpassed 2,000 yuan (240 US
dollars), twice of the region's average.
</P>
<P>
Ngagwang Dunba, director of the Gonchum Villagers' Committee,
said telephone brought much convenience to their life.
</P>
<P>
"More important," he said, "we can get timely information with
telephone, and adjust our business accordingly."
</P>
<P>
Yang Yunlin, from the telecommunication bureau of Nyingchi
Prefecture, said the prefecture used to have only 6 DDD lines. But
Guangdong Province in south China helped build communication
optical fiber linking Lhasa and the prefecture with 50 million
yuan investment and enabled herdsmen to have access to telephone
at home.
</P>
<P>
Although it costs a great deal to extend telephone service in
rural areas, the local telecommunication bureau plans to help
build two to three "telephone villages" in the near future to pave
way for a better life of Tibetan people, Yang said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980513.0237 </DOCNO>
