<HEADLINE> Italian Lower House Approves Government's Economic Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, May 12 (Xinhua) -- The Italian Lower House voted 306 to
192 Tuesday to give green light to the ruling center-left
coalition's new economic and financial plan for 1999-2000, which
was submitted in April.
</P>
<P>
The center-left parties, as well as deputies from the Communist
Refoundation Party and the new Democratic Union for the Republic
supported the plan while the Freedom Front and the Northern League
voted against.
</P>
<P>
The plan is believed to meet no objection in the Senate for
approval because the ruling center-left coalition enjoys a
majority in the house.
</P>
<P>
Under the new guidelines, the government plans to realize a
nine percent growth of the gross domestic product (GDP) in three
years' time.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the government aims to reduce the national debt to
100 percent of the GDP from the present 120 percent of the GDP.
</P>
<P>
It wants to create 700,000 new jobs to cut the unemployment
rate from 12 percent to 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
Environmental protection and disaster prevention were also
given priority in the plan.
</P>
<P>
The government must commit Italy to renegotiate plans for the
use of European Union structural funds and ask Brussels for value
added tax reductions in some labor-intensive sectors, according to
the plan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
