<HEADLINE> Chinese Begin to Accept Mother's Day In Various Ways </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANCHANG, May 13 (Xinhua) -- When a young woman in the city of
Nanchang in east China's Jiangxi Province got a Mother's Day card
from her teen-age daughter, she remembered that she should say
hello to her own mother who was thousands of kilometers away -- so
she did it over the phone.
</P>
<P>
But, carnations, the pink version that is thought to be one of
the best gifts for mothers, seemed to be the clear favorite in
this provincial capital on Mother's Day. One man named Shu in his
40s, who said he never knew about this celebration before, bought
a bunch of carnations for his mother.
</P>
<P>
One florist said that, in a single day, she sold more than 200
carnations.
</P>
<P>
History tells us that an American woman began the holiday 84
years ago, but there are at least 40 countries around the world
that take the second Sunday in May as a banner day for mothers.
</P>
<P>
And now the Chinese have become familiar with the foreign
holiday, especially since it reinforces the traditional Chinese
respect for the elderly.
</P>
<P>
One non-government organization even added an aid program
especially directed at poor mothers in rural areas.
</P>
<P>
The employees of 30 drugstores in Shanghai, the country's
largest metropolis in east China, held charity sales to help the
people with needy mothers living in other places. The authorities
in Nanchang also organized activities for the holiday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
