<HEADLINE> Ukraine to Tighten Budget Deficit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, May 12 (Xinhua) -- Ukrainian President Leonid Kuchma
announced Tuesday his country will limit its budget deficit this
year to 2.5 percent of the projected gross domestic product (GDP).
</P>
<P>
In his state of the nation address, Kuchma said the government
would amend expenditure in some areas and rescind many subsidies
and preferential measures.
</P>
<P>
The president said the GDP growth rate this year would reach
0.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Between 1999 and 2000, the GDP rate will grow 2 or 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
Kuchma admitted Ukraine was facing financial restraints. Since
last year, the country's foreign debt had increased over 50
percent and domestic debt amounted to 13 billion hryvine (6.5
billion U.S. dollars), he said.
</P>
<P>
He told the newly-elected Supreme Rada (parliament) that the
guidelines of Ukraine's market reform would not be changed.
</P>
<P>
The government would improve living standards in the course of
reform, Kuchma promised.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, some 430 new deputies participated in the opening
of the 450-seat legislature. 
</P>
</TEXT>
