<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thick Oil-Bearing Layer Found in Qaidam Basin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XINING, May 13 (Xinhua) -- Scientists successfully verified a
1,727-meter thick oil-bearing layer recently in Lenghu block in
northwest part of Qaidam Basin in northwest China's Qinghai
province.
</P>
<P>
It was a breakthrough for China's oil exploitation, which
prepared abundant resources petroleum industry development in next
century, as well as a leap for petroleum exploitation in northwest
China, according to experts.
</P>
<P>
An official from the Qinghai Petroleum Administration said that
to verify the existence of oil-bearing layer and reserves,
scientists and technicians spent two years and finally found oil
layer at the 5,200-meter spot.
</P>
<P>
Through studies of the Lengke NO.1 oil well, they proved that
the Jurassic system oil-bearing rocks coverage was 23,000 square
kilometers, with 6,000 square meters thicker than 1,000 meters,
and 13,600 square meters thicker than 800 meters.
</P>
<P>
It is said that the Qinghai Oilfield, which took the operation
of Lengke NO.1 oil well, has put in more than one billion yuan in
exploitation work in the recent three years.
</P>
<P>
The Qinghai Oilfield is now the country's fourth largest
oilfield, next only to Sichuan, Shaanxi-Gansu-Ningxia, and Tarim
oilfields. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
