<HEADLINE> Pakistan Rejects Taiwan's Bid for WHO Observer Status </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, May 12 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan's Health Minister Javed
Hashmi has rejected a bid by Taiwan to seek observer status in the
World Health Organization (WHO).
</P>
<P>
A statement issued Tuesday by Pakistan's Health Ministry quoted
Hashmi as saying that "Pakistan and the vast majority of the WHO
members recognize that there is only one China -- the People's
Republic of China -- and that Taiwan is a part of China."
</P>
<P>
Hashmi, who is leading the Pakistani delegation to the current
session of the World Health Assembly in Geneva, said that "being a
province of China, Taiwan does not qualify to join the WHO in any
capacity whatsoever."
</P>
<P>
He recalled the resolutions of the U.N. General Assembly and
the WHO adopted 27 years ago which recognized that "the People's
Republic of China is the sole representative of the Chinese
people."
</P>
<P>
This was, moreover, a political issue not suited for
consideration by the World Health Assembly, the Minister added.
</P>
<P>
Following statements by Pakistan and China, the World Health
Assembly adopted a decision without a vote not to include the item
regarding Taiwan's bid for observer status on its agenda. 
</P>
