<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Most Serious Windy Area Brought Under Control </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, May 13 (Xinhua) -- China's most serious windy area in
northwest China's Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region is now covered
with lush trees and becomes less harmful.
</P>
<P>
The Old Wind Gap, as is called, was measured to have a wind
speed of 40 meter per second, and lies in Tacheng Prefecture, 100
kilometers away from Sino-Kazakhstan border. Snowstorms used to
block the traffic there more than 20 times every winter, causing
12 million yuan in losses annually.
</P>
<P>
Local people would turn pale at the mention of strong
windstorms in winter seasons. Local history book recorded that
Genghis Khan's five hundred armoured cavalrymen lost their lives
in a windstorm in the 13rd century during a mission.
</P>
<P>
However, more than 800 hectares of shelter-forest and 100 ha of
grassland have been developed in the area since 1992 when a
10-year treatment project was started which aims to grow more than
10,000 ha of snow-and-wind-resistant forests, to raise forest
coverage rate to more than 20 percent, and to reduce wind speed by
30 or 40 percent, upon completion, said Liu Shiguang, a local
forestry official.
</P>
<P>
The afforestation efforts have been paid off. In recent years
the strong sandstorms caused only minor losses to the surrounding
areas thanks to the shelterbelt.
</P>
<P>
As more forests and grassland have been able to help slow down
wind speed and reduce evaporation, farmers have cultivated more
than 500 ha of farmland and grow wheat, watermelon and vegetables.
</P>
<P>
"We are confident that we can tame the wind draught at the Old
Wind Gap area, and we are also planning to develop rich wind
energy," Liu said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
