<HEADLINE> IMF Ready to Extend More Loans to Thailand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, May 13 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary Fund
(IMF) is ready to offer additional financial support to Thailand
if the crisis in Indonesia and the region intensifies, the Bangkok
Post Wednesday quoted Thai Finance Minister Tarrin Nimmanhaeminda
as saying.
</P>
<P>
According to the minister, the Thai government has been
contacting the IMF for months about additional funds to shore up
the country's official foreign reserves if needed.
</P>
<P>
However, Tarrin refused to give the exact amount of the fund
available or necessary.
</P>
<P>
Bank of Thailand, the country's central bank, reported that on
April 16, Thailand's official foreign reserves stood at 28.6
billion U.S. dollars with forward obligations of 16.4 billion
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Under the IMF requirement, Thailand must maintain its foreign
reserves at 23-25 billion dollars at the end of this year, with
obligations reduced to 9 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Economists agreed that additional foreign funds would be needed
to support Thailand's foreign reserves if the regional situation
deteriorates and leads to increased capital flight and pressure on
the local currency baht.
</P>
<P>
Tarrin said Thailand was closely watching the events in
Indonesia and the impact on currency volatility in the region.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia has been wracked by student protests and rioting over
the past few weeks, reflecting growing social unrest over the
country's economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
Tarrin said the recent events in the region had signaled that a
regional economic recovery had not yet taken hold.
</P>
<P>
this could in turn affect Thailand's own efforts toward
recovery, he added. 
</P>
