Pischetsrieder also noted that only BMW now had an agreement with
British engine maker Rolls-Royce PLC on the exclusive right to the
name of Rolls-Royce.
</P>
<P>
Pischetsrieder's remarks came after the bidding war for the
British noble brand took a surprise turn last Thursday after
Vickers, the parent firm of Rolls-Royce Motor Cars, turned to
support Volkswagen to take over the British carmaker.
</P>
<P>
The aboutface was due to an improved bid from VW, worth 430
million pounds (713.2 million U.S. dollars), well above the 340
million pounds (564 million dollars) offered by BMW.
</P>
<P>
BMW had previously engaged in exclusive talks with Vickers on
the planned takeover. But the British company argued that the
higher offer made by Volkswagen would bring more benefits to its
shareholders.
</P>
<P>
A decision is due to be made by a special shareholders meeting
of the British company on June 4.  
</P>
