<DOCNO> XIE19980513.0261 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canadians' Incomes Down in Early 1990s </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, May 12 (Xinhua) -- The recession of the early 1990s
lowered incomes of Canadians by six percent between 1990 and 1995,
wiping out gains made during the second half of 1980s, Statistics
Canada said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
After adjustment for inflation, the average income received by
Canadians in 1995 was 25,196 Canadian dollars (17,637
U.S.dollars), almost the same as that received in 1985 and
slightly below the level of 1980.
</P>
<P>
The average income of men was 7.8 percent below their average
income in 1990, while the average income of women saw a 2.1
percent drop from 1990, the statistics agency said in its 11th
report from the 1996 census.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, Canadians' employment income continued to
decline as a proportion of total income. In 1995, employment
income accounted for 75 cents for every dollar of income, down
from 78 cents in 1990 and 86 cents in 1970.
</P>
<P>
The share of government transfer payments, such as old-age
pensions and unemployment insurance benefits, doubled over the
past quarter century.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, these transfers contributed 14 cents of every dollar
of income, compared with 11 cents in 1990 and less than seven
cents in 1970.
</P>
<P>
"This increase resulted from changes in both social security
programs and the demographic composition of the population," the
agency said.
</P>
<P>
Between 1971 and 1996, Canada's total population increased 34
percent, while the population aged over 65 and older, which
received many of the transfer payments, more than doubled.
</P>
<P>
In the first half of 1990s, the incidence of low income among
families increased from 13 percent in 1990 to 16 percent in 1995.
</P>
<P>
"The rate was highest among lone-parent families, aboriginal
people and the visible minority population," the agency noted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980513.0262 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-13 </DATE_TIME>
