<HEADLINE> UK Rail Firms Urged to Improve Performance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 12 (Xinhua) -- Britain's rail companies were
criticized for their poor performance after official figures
showed that fewer trains ran on time last year, national
newspapers reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that figures provided by the Office of
Passenger Rail Franchising indicated punctuality worsened on more
than two thirds of routes in the year to March, the first year in
which all routes were under private management.
</P>
<P>
John Prescott, the Deputy Prime Minister, was reported as
describing the operators' record as "unacceptable", and promising
that next month's transport White Paper would set out ways of
achieving higher standards.
</P>
<P>
"Poor performers must take immediate steps to improve their
performance and to maintain levels throughout the year," Prescott
said.
</P>
<P>
Reports said that those firms that performed worst were fined
up to 1.35 million pounds (2.2 million U.S. dollars), but they
blamed problems caused by maintenance work for the deterioration
in time-keeping.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the rail firms said that the volume of
passengers had risen seven percent last year, prompting 30,000
extra trains. The capacity of the system's infrastructure to cope
with such expansion was an increasing cause of concern.  
</P>
</TEXT>
