<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> African Bankers Eye Boom of Small Loans for Poor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, May 12 (Xinhua) -- Top banking experts from 15
African countries gathered here Tuesday to explore the means to
boost small loans for the poor as part of anti-poverty campaign
across the continent.
</P>
<P>
The three-day African Conference on the Commercialization of
Micro-finance brings together more than 130 participants from
countries such as Ghana, Kenya, Mozambique, Namibia, South
Africa, Tanzania, Uganda, Zambia and Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
"In the recent years, commercial bankers in Africa have become
increasingly interested in micro-finance mainly due to the
potential size of the market and the ability of micro-lending
methodologies in reaching large numbers of poor clients more
effectively," said the U.S. Agency for International Development
(USAID).
</P>
<P>
"Micro-finance is a good business for Africa" and has been
expanding quickly in the past seven years, said Bethuel Kiplagat,
chairman of Kenya Rural Enterprise Program (K-REP) which is one
of the leading five micro-finance organizations in Kenya.
</P>
<P>
"Some seven years ago it was unthinkable that hard-nosed
bankers and welfare-oriented development workers like me could
sit a round table... to discuss business prospects for making
small loans to and accepting small deposits from the poor at a
profit," he recalled.
</P>
<P>
"The collective wealth of the poor in Africa is enormous, just
as their demand for appropriate financial services," he concluded
in a key-note speech.
</P>
<P>
While he noted a major challenge facing African bankers is how
to increase their scale of operations since "most of the
micro-finance institutions in Africa have less than 20,000
clients."
</P>
<P>
"The low scale of operation of most micro-finance institutions
limits their ability to achieve financial sustainability.
Micro-finance organizations must therefore strive to achieve high
volumes of loan advances and savings," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Kiplagat quoted the 1997 Microcredit Summit report as saying
that eight million very poor families worldwide are already
receiving credit for self-employment, leaving 92 million families
still to be reached by 2005. Most of them live in the Third
World.
</P>
<P>
The report said about 21.6 billion U.S. Dollars will be
required to meet the estimated micro-credit needs from the poor.
</P>
<P>
The conference to end Thursday is sponsored by the USAID, the
British Department For International Development (DFID), Citicorp
Foundation and the World Bank. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
