<HEADLINE> Chinese Embassy Refutes So-Called "China Threat" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, May 12 (Xinhua) -- Charge D'affaires Ad Interim of
the Chinese Embassy in India Lin Shanglin rejected here Tuesday
what he called the recent slanderous rumors of a "China Threat" by
some Indians. He reiterated China's independent foreign policy of
peace.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a press conference at the embassy, Lin said China is
now fully dedicated to its modernization drive as well as reforms
and opening up. This needed a long-term peaceful international
environment, particularly a good surrounding environment.
</P>
<P>
He said China has always adhered to an independent policy of
peace and striving to develop a friendly relationship with all
other nations on the basis of the Five Principles of Peaceful
Coexistense.
</P>
<P>
Lin said that recently some Indians had insisted on spreading
the rumor of the so-called "China Threat". The groundless
accusation has not only hurt the feelings of the Chinese people,
but has undermined the atmosphere favorable to improving
Sino-Indian ties and the furtherance of bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
He said Chinese President Jiang Zemin's successful visit to
India at the end of 1996 brought the Sino-Indian ties into a new
stage of development at the turn of the century.
</P>
<P>
Leaders of the two countries established a constructive
partership geared toward the 21st century on the basis of the Five
Principles of Peaceful Coexistense, and reached broad consensus on
high-level exchanges of visits and cooperation in a range of
fields such as economy, trade, science and technology.
</P>
<P>
Lin said the development of good-neighborly and cooperative
ties between China and India, as the two most populous nations in
the world, not only conforms to the basic interests of the two
peoples, but also to the needs of peace and stability in the
region and the world at large.
</P>
<P>
Speaking of the border problems left over by history between
the two nations, Lin said China has always taken a positive stand
toward the problems.
</P>
<P>
He said China hoped the two sides would continue to seek fair
and reasonable solutions to the border issues in the spirit of
mutual understanding and compromise.
</P>
<P>
Lin said Sino-Indian ties had achieved a marked improvement
thanks to the joint efforts of the two countries. He hoped both
sides would cherish the hard-won improvement and work to enhance
bilateral ties and friendship by both words and actions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
