<HEADLINE> Burundi Peace Talks to Resume in June </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, May 12 (Xinhua) -- The stalled negotiations
between the Burundi military authority and leaders of Great Lakes
countries will resume next month, media reports said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Julius Nyerere, the international mediator in the Burundi
political conflict, has set June 15 as the date for the formal
start of the negotiations, according to a statement issued here
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The statement said the negotiations involving all warring
parties of Burundi will be held in the farming town of Arusha in
northern Tanzania on June 15.
</P>
<P>
The Burundi peace talks were stalled last year after the
Burundi military authority led by Pierre Buyoya said it had no
faith in Nyerere, who is an advocate of imposing economic
sanctions on Burundi.
</P>
<P>
East and central African countries backed by the Organization
of African Unity (OAU) have imposed economic sanctions on Burundi
since August of 1996 after Major Buyoya toppled a civilian
government of President Ntibantunganya in July of the year.
</P>
<P>
Nyerere insisted that one of the conditions to resume Burundi
peace talks is the release of former Burundi presidents,
Jean-Baptiste Bagaza and Sylvestre Ntibantunganya, and also
Speaker of the Burundi National Assembly Leonce Ngendakumana.
</P>
<P>
According to Nyerere, the conditions, set during the last
Great Lakes summit in Kampala last year, should be respected
first.
</P>
<P>
Bagaza and Ngendakumana were freed from house arrest earlier
this year, paving the way for the resumption of peace talks. But
Buyoya is reported to be reluctant to accept Nyerere as the
mediator. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
