<HEADLINE> Israel's New Chief of General Staff Approved </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, May 12 (Xinhua) -- Israeli cabinet on Tuesday
approved the nomination of Major General Shaul Mofaz as next chief
of general staff of the Israel Defense Forces (IDF).
</P>
<P>
Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai submitted the nomination
Monday to cabinet, saying that the two top candidates, Mofaz and
Major General Matan Vilani, were both qualified, but he considered
Mofaz more suitable.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu said that since the chief of
general staff would have to work closely together with the
defense minister, he is in favor of Mordechai's choice.
</P>
<P>
Mofaz, a father of two, is to replace the current chief of
general staff, Amnon Lipkin Shahak, who will step down on July 9.
</P>
<P>
Mofaz, born in Tehran, Iran in 1948, immigrated to
Israel at age nine with his family. He had been living in the
southern city of Eilat until he was sent to an agriculture high
school in the north of the country.
</P>
<P>
He has a bachelor's degree in business administration from
Israeli Bar-Ilan University and is a graduate of the U.S. Marine
Corps Command and Staff College.
</P>
<P>
First drafted to the paratroops of the IDF in 1966, he rose
through the ranks to brigadier-general and led an armored
division. He then commanded the troops in south Lebanon and in
August 1993 was promoted to major general and appointed the IDf
commander in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
In late 1994, Mofaz became head of the southern command of
the IDF and held this post until March 1996, when he became head
of the IDF Planning Branch. Last year, he was named deputy chief
of general staff.
</P>
<P>
Mordechai has been cultivating Mofaz since he assumed the
defense portfolio two years ago. The other candidate, Vilani, is
more popular in the army. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
