<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Envoy to Visit Lebanon on Israeli Offer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, May 12 (Xinhua) -- Russian special Middle East envoy
Viktor Possevalyuk is expected to visit Lebanon on Wednesday in
his fresh efforts to activate the Lebanese and Syrian tracks in
peace process stalled for over two years.
</P>
<P>
During his stay in Beirut, Possevalyuk will hold talks with
Lebanese leaders on regional affairs, especially the recent
Israeli withdrawal offer.
</P>
<P>
On April 1, Israeli cabinet formally endorsed the 20-year-old
United Nations resolution 425 and offered to withdraw troops from
south Lebanon if Lebanese government agrees to provide security
for Israeli border areas.
</P>
<P>
However, Lebanon and Syria, which agreed to coordinate stances
in the peace process, firmly rejected the offer, insisting on an
unconditional Israeli pullout from south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Israel, after two invasions of Lebanon, carved out a
1,200-square-kilometer border strip in the south in 1985 as
security zone, under the pretext of protecting its northern areas
from cross-border guerrilla attacks.
</P>
<P>
Syria, which has 40,000 troops in Lebanon, seeks a
comprehensive peace deal that would also involve an Israeli
withdrawal from the Golan Heights, captured from Syria in the 1967
Middle East war.
</P>
<P>
The Russian envoy will convey a message from Russian Foreign
Minister Yevgeny Primakov to his Lebanese counterpart Farez Boueiz
on Russian positions over the Israeli offer.
</P>
<P>
After visiting Lebanon, he will go to Damascus and confer with
Syrian leaders over the issue.
</P>
<P>
It is not known if Possevalyuk will carry any initiatives to
restart the Syrian and Lebanese peace talks with Israel, which
have been deadlocked since the hardline Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu came to power in June, 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980513.0281 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EC Vice-President Meets H.K. Trade Secretary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, May 12 (Xinhua) -- European Commission Vice-President
Sir Leon Brittan met on Tuesday Chau Tak Hay, Hong Kong's
secretary for trade and industry.
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong trade official assured Brittan that Hong Kong
would continue to promote multilateral trade liberalization and
that events had shown that Hong Kong had been truly exercising
autonomy in its external trade policy.
</P>
<P>
Chau, who is scheduled to fly to Geneva for a series of
bilateral meetings with trade officials of other countries in the
context of the World Trade Organization (WTO), also reiterated
Hong Kong's determination to protect intellectual property rights
by combating pirated CDs.
</P>
<P>
He said that Hong Kong had recently introduced administrative
and legislative measures to reinforce the protection of
intellectual property rights in respect of CDs in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong trade secretary told the commission
vice-president that Hong Kong would support a WTO ministerial
declaration in Geneva next week which would enable a new round of
comprehensive multilateral trade negotiations to be launched
before the start of the new century.
</P>
<P>
Chau expressed satisfaction at the currently sound trade and
economic relations between Hong Kong and the 15-nation European
Union and expected that bilateral cooperation would be furthered.
</P>
<P>
The commission vice-president and the Hong Kong trade secretary
also discussed issues such as electronic commerce and regionalism
on the multilateral trading system.  
</P>
</TEXT>
