<HEADLINE> Turkish Parliament Launches Second Probe of PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, May 12 (Xinhua) -- Turkish parliament voted Tuesday to
launch a second probe into allegations that Prime Minister Mesut
Yilmaz cost state money by awarding consulting work to private
firms.
</P>
<P>
The Parliament launched its first investigation in April into
Yilmaz's personal wealth on allegations that he had omitted some
shares in the Finans Bank between 1990 and 1995.
</P>
<P>
The inquiries were both urged by his bitter rival ex-premier
Tansu Ciller's True Path Party.
</P>
<P>
In the latest case, Ciller's party accused Yilmaz of awarding
a feasibility study for the construction of a second Istanbul
airport to two private firms instead of government agencies,
arguing that the government agencies could do the same job 18.4
million U.S. dollars cheaper.
</P>
<P>
A 15-member commission will be set up to conduct the inquiry,
which will last two months and political parties will name their
candidates for the panel.
</P>
<P>
It was believed that the two inquiries against Yilmaz were a
retaliation for the probe now underway into Ciller's private
property. 
</P>
</TEXT>
