<HEADLINE> Syria, Lebanon Coordinate Stances on Israeli Offer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAMASCUS, May 12 (Xinhua) -- Syrian and Lebanese held a meeting
here Tuesday to coordinate their stance on the latest developments
in the Middle East, particularly the Israeli offer of conditional
withdrawal from south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Syrian Vice President Abdul-Halim Khaddam and Minister of
Foreign Affairs Farouq al-Sharaa met the visiting Lebanese Prime
Minister Rafik Hariri and Parliament Speaker Nabih Berri as part
of the consultations between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Hariri briefed the meeting the results of his recent visit to
Paris and his talks with French President Jacques Chirac,
according to informed sources here.
</P>
<P>
The viewpoints were identical on most of the issues discussed
and the two sides agreed on the continuation of cooperation in the
face of the Israeli maneuver which aims to "eviscerate the U.N.
Security Council resolution 425."
</P>
<P>
Syria and Lebanon have been conducting intensive consultations
since Israel declared its intention to implement the resolution
and quit south Lebanon provided security arrangements are worked
out with Lebanese government.
</P>
<P>
The two countries deemed Israel's offer "a mere maneuver" that
aims to drive a wedge between Syria and Lebanon and evade a
sincere and unconditional implementation of the resolution.
</P>
<P>
Syria and Lebanon agreed to launch a large scale diplomatic
campaign to explain their positions on the Israeli designs and on
the rejection of any talks with Israel about the security
arrangements under Israeli request. 
</P>
</TEXT>
