<HEADLINE> Jordan Jails Pro-Iraq Opposition Leader </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, May 12 (Xinhua) -- A prominent opposition leader, Leith
Shbeilat, was convicted of inciting pro-Iraqi "illegal gathering"
and sentenced to nine months in jail Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Jordan's State Security Court said Tuesday that it had
"sufficient" evidence that Shbeilat, former president of Jordan
Engineers Association, was the instigator of the February riot in
the city of Ma'an, some 250 kilometers south of the capital,
official Radio Jordan reported.
</P>
<P>
Shbeilat made a "sensational" sermon to the Ma'an prayers at
its main Mosque on February 20, the radio said, just a day before
a pro-Iraq riot there, which led to one death and 23 injuries.
</P>
<P>
Shbeilat was arrested on his way from Ma'an to Amman, but no
time was given.
</P>
<P>
The opposition leader was put into prison twice, in 1992 and
1996, on charges of lese majeste and treason respectively, and was
pardoned twice by King Hussein. 
