<HEADLINE> Insecurity in Angola Creates 70,000 New Refugees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, May 12 (Xinhua) -- Angolan Deputy Minister of
Assistance and Social Reintegration Eufrazina Maiato said here
Tuesday that insecurity ensuing from armed operations by remnants
of UNITA soldiers has created 70,000 more refugees in the
country.
</P>
<P>
She told the press that the militiamen of the former rebel
National Union for the Total Independence of Angola (UNITA) have
launched attacks in Bie, Huambo and Benguela provinces in central
Angola, Luanda-Norte and Lunda-Sul provinces in the northeast and
Huila in the south, displacing many families and putting their
lives in great difficulties.
</P>
<P>
This situation is "unexpected" and disturbed the
implementation of the national rehabilitation program, she said,
adding that the United Nations mission in Angola are not prepared
for the emergency, thus having difficulty in providing assistance
to the refugees, the Angola News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
International aid agencies are not able to reach all the
refugees areas due to security reasons, Maiato said.
</P>
<P>
Reports said the sabotage by UNITA militiamen has been on the
rise recently and the situation is deteriorating despite repeated
government warnings.
</P>
<P>
Arao Chiteculo, Deputy Governor of Huambo Province, revealed
Tuesday to the press that 10 people, including Vice-Mayor of
Caala city and national Police Commander of Kuima town, had died
in two attacks on buses within four days' time, and nine others
wounded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
