<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> LIFFE And Aex Launch FTSE Eurotop 100 Index Future </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 12 (Xinhua) -- The London Financial Futures and
Options Exchange (LIFFE) and Amsterdam Exchanges (AEX)
respectively launched Tuesday new futures and options on the FTSE
Eurotop 100 index, according to an announcement released here.
</P>
<P>
The FTSE Eurotop 100 is an index of the 100 most liquid stocks
in the largest stock markets in Europe. It currently covers the
nine largest markets in UK, Germany, France, Switzerland,
Netherland, Italy, Sweden, Spain and Belgium.
</P>
<P>
The Index - calculated by FTSE International - is Europe's
benchmark for trading the performance of the most liquid major
companies in Europe's highest capitalized markets.
</P>
<P>
By listing futures on the FTSE Europtop 100 Index, LIFFE will
be able to provide users with an instrument to trade the most
liquid stocks listed on Europe's major equity markets in a single
transaction.
</P>
<P>
LIFFE is listing the futures as proprietary traders and hedgers
are increasingly focusing on Europe's equity markets in the run-up
to Economic and Monetary Union and a time of declining European
bond yields.
</P>
<P>
LIFFE and AEX intend introducing futures and options on the
broader based FTSE Eurotop 300 Index early in 1999 as the market
for pan-European products develops.
</P>
<P>
Mark Makepeace, Managing Director of FTSE International, said:
"European monetary union has begun. You can now trade on Amsterdam
Exchanges and LIFFE."
</P>
<P>
"These contracts, based on 100 stocks, not only provide much
greater flexibility in designing pan-European products -
importantly they also track the established European benchmark
indices," he added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980513.0289 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: UK Manufacturing in Technical Recession </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 12 (Xinhua) -- The UK's manufacturing output fell
for the second consecutive quarter, officially confirming that the
sector is now mired in recession.
</P>
<P>
Factory output fell by 0.1 percent in the first three months of
this year following a 0.5 percent drop in the previous quarter,
according to the latest official figures by the Office of National
Statistics.
</P>
<P>
Depressed by the strength of the pound, which makes exports
more expensive and imports cheaper, manufacturing production has
been flat since last summer.
</P>
<P>
Economic analysts said that despite the recent slide in the
value of the currency, it remained at levels that would continue
to damage exporters.
</P>
<P>
Further evidence that the slowdown is beginning to spread to
other parts of the economy emerged in the latest British Retail
Consortium survey of high street sales.
</P>
<P>
The value of sales on a like-for-like basis rose 5.7 percent in
the year to April, up from just 0.4 percent in the previous month.
But adjusting for the late Easter this year by taking the two
months together suggested sales growth had slowed.
</P>
<P>
Nervousness about the economic outlook is reaching investors,
with the latest Merrill Lynch/Gallup survey of fund managers
revealing they have become net sellers of commercial property for
the first time in two years.
</P>
<P>
Trevor Cheetham, of Merrill Lynch, said this reflected a belief
that the economic cycle is turning downwards with investors
switching into gilts.
</P>
<P>
An UK economist at Nikko Europe said: "The main unanswered
question is 'How deep the recession will be?'"
</P>
<P>
It is also believed here that Manufacturing is only 20 percent
of UK's economy but against the background of a slowing service
sector the danger is that the psychological effect of a recession
in manufacturing could turn the expected soft landing for the
economy into a hard one.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980513.0290 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Air China, Northwest Airlines to Share Codes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, May 12 (Xinhua) -- China's flag carrier Air China and
U.S. Northwest Airlines signed a commercial cooperation agreement
here on Tuesday to benefit from the code-sharing service.
</P>
<P>
According to the accord, Air China's flight codes will be put
on Northwest's China-U.S. flights and on certain U.S. domestic
flights, and Northwest's flight codes on Air China's service
between China and the U.S.
</P>
<P>
The two sides will also cooperate in flight schedules and
connections, computer reservation systems (CRS) linkage, through
check-in and "seamless" service including downline seat
assignments and boarding passes, reciprocal frequent flyer
programs and joint marketing programs.
</P>
<P>
The code-sharing service is made available under the China-U.S.
bilateral aviation agreement.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing-based Air China, the largest airline in China,
currently operates round-trip service from Beijing and Shanghai to
San Francisco and New York's John F. Kennedy Airport. It plans to
inaugurate non-stop service between China and Los Angeles in June.
</P>
<P>
Northwest, a major U.S. airline with the longest history of
service between the United States and Asia since 1947, operates
the Detroit-Beijing service five times weekly and provides the
only non-stop service by a U.S. airline between North America and
China.
</P>
<P>
The agreement also provides for the opportunity for Air China
to share codes with Northwest's partners Continental Airlines,
Alaska Airlines and America West Airlines.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
