<HEADLINE> S. Leonean Bishop Says No Contact with Koroma </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, May 12 (Xinhua) -- Amidst reports that the leader of
Sierra Leone's former military junta, Johnny Paul Koroma, has
offered surrender to the Catholic mission in the country, the
bishop involved denied Tuesday any contact with the fugitive man.
</P>
<P>
"I have not contacted with Johnny Paul Koroma," said Bishop
George Biguzzi, quoted by a British Broadcasting Corporation
report monitored here.
</P>
<P>
The bishop of the Catholic Dioceses in Makeni, northern Sierra
Leone added the reports of any contact by Koroma who he does not
know personally were "rumors and speculations".
</P>
<P>
If Koroma wants to surrender, he should first inform the
president who has the last and final word, he said.
</P>
<P>
The bishop also promised that as a religious person, he would do
according to the directive of the presidency in the interest of
the country.
</P>
<P>
It has been widely reported that Koroma has offered to
surrender via the Catholic bishop.
</P>
<P>
The west African peacekeeping force known as ECOMOG, which
ousted Koroma's military junta three months ago, has said the
alleged development is encouraging.
</P>
<P>
Koroma resorted to Bishop Biguzzi for fear of his life and
that of his family.
</P>
<P>
According to the bishop, the people in his dioceses are still
suffering as a result of continued attacks by remnants of the
junta forces and allied rebels.
</P>
<P>
Only on Monday, he said, houses were burnt in some villages,
people were killed and others injured.
</P>
<P>
Koroma, who seized power from the elected government of
President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah last May, was dislodged in
mid-February by the Nigerian-led ECOMOG forces.
</P>
<P>
While he ran out of the net of the sub-regional force,
remnants of his army, along with the Revolutionary United Front
(RUF) rebels, have since been waging war against the advancing
ECOMOG in the eastern and northern parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
ECOMOG forces are intensifying the mopping up exercise and
progress has been reported in the past few days.  
</P>
</TEXT>
