<HEADLINE> U.S. Forecasts Winter Wheat Crop down 9 percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 12 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Agriculture Department
predicted here Tuesday that the American farmers will harvest a
winter wheat crop down 9 percent from last year at 1.71 billion
bushels.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the early predictions for this country's corn crop,
indicated farmers will have 9.64 billion bushels, which would be
the second-largest on record. Soybean production is tentatively
projected at 2.8 billion bushels, up 3 percent from last year's
record.
</P>
<P>
Farmers are expected to harvest over 1 million acres less
winter wheat than last year, when averages prices topped 4 U.S.
dollars a bushel. This year's crop could sell at just over 3
dollars a bushel, leading many growers to switch to other crops.
</P>
<P>
Kansas, the leading winter wheat producing state, expects a
crop of about 377.4 million bushels, down from 506 million bushels
in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Including Spring wheat just now being planted, total U.S. wheat
production this year is projected at 2.3 billion bushels, a 7
percent drop from last year.
</P>
<P>
Despite the lower crop estimate, prices will remain depressed
due to higher level in storage from last year and export demand is
weak. At the same time, U.S. growers face a strong challenge from
the European Union.
</P>
<P>
With wheat, corn price projections are down, the Agriculture
Department predicts prices could go as low as 2.05 dollars a
bushel, compared to 2.71 dollars two years ago.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
