<HEADLINE> Hussein Slaps Israel for Rejecting U.S. Idea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, May 12 (Xinhua) -- Jordan's King Hussein on Tuesday
criticized Israel for rejecting a U.S. proposal aimed at reviving
the stalled Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
"I think Israel owes too much to the United States as
it is the case of many of our friends in the region," the
king told reporters after inaugurating the Al Karamah Dam in
the Jordan Valley, some 50 kilometers northwest of Amman.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. proposal, calling for a 13.1 percent more Israeli
withdrawal from the West Bank, has been accepted by the
Palestinian side but rejected by Israel, who insisted on no more
than 9 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian side has done its uttermost and taken a
"constructive" stand by accepting the proposal while Israel
appears aloof and irresponsible, he said.
</P>
<P>
The king then pinned hope on the U.S. efforts to remove the
current obstacles to bring forth peace for the region based on
mutual respect.
</P>
<P>
"We are waiting for what the U.S. can do as a partner
to peace making," added the king.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian-Israeli negotiations was deadlocked last March
due to Jewish settlement expansion in Arab East Jerusalem.
</P>
