<HEADLINE> European Shares Down on Interest Rates Concerns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 12 (Xinhua) -- Major stock markets in Europe all
suspended Monday's rally and ended sharply lower Tuesday, dragged
down by consolidation, Wall Street's mixed opening and fears over
U.S. interest rates.
</P>
<P>
Britain's FTSE 100 index of leading shares gave up all Monday's
gains and was driven back below the 6,000-point level in
futures-led trade amid worries about the outlook for U.S. interest
rates.
</P>
<P>
But dealers said that selling pressure was light among leading
shares, with around 60 percent of trade in non-FTSE stocks.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, some investors were sidelined ahead of U.S. retail
sales and inflation figures and UK jobless and earning numbers
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In Frankfurt, German shares ended 44.34 points or 0.83 percent
down at 5,297.35 on the DAX-30 index as the market continued to
consolidate.
</P>
<P>
"We are moving lower but there is no real selling pressure and
the DAX-30 index remains pinned in a 5,200-5,300 range," said one
dealer.
</P>
<P>
On the Paris bourse, the CAC-40 index retreated from Monday's
new record closing high and closed 29.91 points or 0.74 percent
down at 3,987.33 as the market booked profits made in the 2.84
percent rise in the previous session. 
</P>
