<HEADLINE> Clinton Leaves for Europe Tour </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 12 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton left
here for Germany Tuesday on a week-long trip to Europe on his Air
Force One plane and is to attend the annual summit of the G-8
countries in Britain.
</P>
<P>
Clinton planned to spend two days in Germany, where he will
meet with Chancellor Helmut Kohl and participate in ceremonies
marking the 50th anniversary of the Berlin airlift, an operation
staged by the Western allies in 1948-49 to bring supplies to
West Berlin during a blockade by Soviet troops.
</P>
<P>
He will go to Birmingham, England, to join leaders from
Britain, Canada, France, Germany, Italy, Japan and Russia for the
summit from May 15 to 17.
</P>
<P>
Just hours before his departure for Europe, Clinton unveiled
his International Crime Control Strategy Tuesday at the White
House, calling for 289 million U.S. dollars to help combat drug
trafficking and other border-crossing crimes.
</P>
<P>
At the G-8 summit, those nations will begin working on a plan
to cooperate on fighting international crime.
</P>
<P>
"We will work with other nations to create a worldwide dragnet
capability to promptly arrest and extradite fugitives from
justice," Clinton said at the White House.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. will work to ensure other nations are also ready to
fight international crime with global standards and goals,
training and technical aid, and programs to modernize criminal
laws elsewhere, added Clinton.
</P>
<P>
He is scheduled to visit Geneva, Switzerland, on May 18 for
ceremonies marking the 50th anniversary of the World Trade
Organization before returning to Washington. 
</P>
</TEXT>
