<HEADLINE> S.Africa, Lesotho Discuss Cross-Border Shootings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, May 12 (Xinhua) -- South African and Lesotho
ministers Tuesday met a the Maluti military barracks near
Matatiele in South Africa's Eastern Cape Province to discuss
recent cross-border shootings which left four South Africans dead
and several others injured.
</P>
<P>
"The discussions were fruitful," South African Press
Association quoted Lesotho Foreign Minister Kelebone Maope as
saying.
</P>
<P>
Maope led the Lesotho delegation while his South African
counterpart, Alfred Nzo, led the South African team to the
meeting.
</P>
<P>
The South African delegation also included Defense Minister
Joe Modise, and Safety and Security Minister Sydney Mufamadi.
</P>
<P>
Maope said the meeting was important for Lesotho to clear
impressions that Lesotho nationals had invaded South African
territory.
</P>
<P>
He said a meeting will soon be held to consider the
recommendations of a task team appointed immediately after the
May 1 incident, adding that the Lesotho government was impressed
with progress being made in resolving the cross-border problem.
</P>
<P>
In the May 1 incident, four South Africans were killed and
several others wree injured as they tried to cross into Lesotho
to recover their stolen cattle.
</P>
<P>
Maope said his government is pleased with the results of a
joint monitoring operation betwen South Africa's Kwazulu-Natal
and Lesotho. "We are already noticing downward trends in the
criminal activity along that route and we hope the same results
will be achieved on the Eastern Cape-Lesotho cross-border issue."
</P>
</TEXT>
