<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chief Justice Questions Bills to Federalize Juvenile </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 12 (Xinhua) -- Chief Justice William H.
Rehnquist of the United States Supreme Court raised questions
about efforts in Congress to federalize the prosecutions of
juveniles who are made to stand trial as adults.
</P>
<P>
In a speech to the American Law Institute, the nation's top
judge described two bills now before Congress as "especially
troubling" because they would "increase substantially the
potential workload of the federal judiciary" without a showing
that state courts cannot handle such cases just as well or better.
</P>
<P>
"Both bills eliminate the traditional preference for state
prosecutions of juvenile defendants," Rehnquist said, and they
"would eviscerate this traditional deference to state
prosecutions."
</P>
<P>
Copies of his Monday speech were distributed by Supreme Court
officials Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Current law favors state prosecutions unless a state's juvenile
programs are deemed inadequate or a minor's violent crime or
drug-trafficking offense raises some substantial federal interest.
</P>
<P>
A bill pending before the Senate would let federal prosecutors
treat juveniles 14 and older as adults for a variety of criminal
violations. A corresponding bill in the House would apply to
juveniles 13 and older if the attorney general approved of a
prosecution.
</P>
<P>
The House bill also would lower the age -- from 18 to 16 -- at
which the federal government can seek the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
"Whether these policies are wise ones is debatable, but what is
not debatable is that, if implemented, they will significantly add
to the caseload burdens of the federal judiciary," the chief
justice said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980513.0310 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-13 </DATE_TIME>
