<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Report: World Population Hits 6 Billion in 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 12 (Xinhua) -- The world population, growing by
80 million a year, will hit 6 billion next year and is expected to
be doubled in the next 50 years, said a population research body
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
In an annual assessment of global trends, the Population
Reference Bureau, a nonprofit research organization, also expected
that the current world, which adds a billion people every 12 or 13
years, will have a declining birth rate worldwide in the coming
years.
</P>
<P>
The report said the size of the world population will be
decided by the number of children women would have. If women
average two children, the population would rise to 9.4 billion by
2050, and then reach 11 billion in the following century.
</P>
<P>
However, if the average would be 2.5 children, the world
population would grow to 11.2 billion in 2050 and 27 billion by
2150. And if the rate would be 1.6, the population would decline
in the 21st century, peaking at 7.7 billion in 2050 and then
dropping to 3.6 billion by 2150.
</P>
<P>
The report said most industrial nations would maintain their
population size, with the size in some countries shrinking, but
the number of people in most developing countries will continue to
increase.
</P>
<P>
The report said the urbanization, rising educational
attainment, and lower infant mortality often greatly contribute to
a growing desire for smaller families. And family planning use has
helped couples to achieve the family size they wish.
</P>
<P>
But population will grow for a long time even if each couple
only have two children because of the big group of child-bearing
young women.
</P>
<P>
At present, there are 2 billion young people, about 90 percent
of them in developing countries, are entering or about to enter
their child-bearing years. Each year 18 percent of women 15 to 19
years of age give birth in Middle Africa; 5 percent in Southeast
Asia; and 1 percent in Western Europe, the report said. In
sub-Saharan Africa, the total fertility rate remains very high at
nearly 6 live births per woman.
</P>
<P>
In terms of ranking, the world's four largest nations -- China,
India, the United States and Indonesia -- will retain those places
in 2025, the bureau said. But Pakistan will move from the seventh
to fifth place, Nigeria will rise from 10th to seventh, Mexico
will jump from 11th to ninth and Bangladesh from ninth to eighth.
</P>
<P>
Current sixth-position Russia will fall to 10th place in 2025,
Japan, now eighth, will drop to 11th and Brazil, from fifth to
sixth. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980513.0312 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-13 </DATE_TIME>
