<HEADLINE> U.S. President Clinton to Visit Germany </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BERLIN, May 12 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton will
start a European trip with a visit to Germany Wednesday and
Thursday, where he will highlight new prospects for transatlantic
relations between the United States and Europe, U.S. Ambassador to
Germany John Kornblum said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Clinton will attend ceremonies Thursday at the Tempelhof
Airport of Berlin marking the 50th anniversary of the Berlin
airlift, an operation staged by the Western allies in 1948-49 to
bring supplies to the then West Berlin during a blockade by Soviet
troops.
</P>
<P>
He will also hold talks with German Chancellor Helmut Kohl in
the historic city of Potsdam to discuss a wide range of issues
including NATO and EU expansions, European integration,
U.S.-German ties, as well as situations in the Middle East, Bosnia
and Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders would also exchange views for the upcoming
Group of Eight (G-8) summit to be held in Birmingham, England,
later this week which both of them will attend, German officials
said.
</P>
<P>
During the visit, which is his third one to the country since
1994, Clinton is also due to meet Gerhard Schroeder, the Social
Democratic chancellor candidate who will challenge Kohl in the
German national elections on September 27.
</P>
<P>
With his visit focusing on eastern Germany this time, the U.S.
president is also expected to address special social problems
facing the region in a speech to be delivered in the eastern
German town of Eisenach Thursday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
