<DOCNO> XIE19980513.0314 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. to Try to Revive Mideast Summit: Albright </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 12 (Xinhua) -- Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright said Tuesday that she would re-issue invitations to the
Israeli and Palestinian leaders to Washington for a summit if she
could reach agreement with Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu on Wednesday's talks.
</P>
<P>
But she insisted a U.S. proposal on Israel's pullback from 13
percent of the West Bank would not be watered down for that
purpose.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the National Press Club, Albright said she hoped
"there is a way that we can get this (peace) process back on track
and in fact re-issue the invitation for accelerated permanent
status talks to be held under President (Bill) Clinton's auspices
in Washington very soon."
</P>
<P>
Albright described herself as "an eternal optimist" and said
she was looking forward to the Wednesday meeting with Netanyahu,
which is aimed at laying the ground for final Israeli-Palestinian
peace talks.
</P>
<P>
The secretary said a 13 percent Israeli withdrawal from the
West Bank is the "only way" to end a 15-month impasse and
re-launch talks with the Palestinian Authority on a permanent
settlement.
</P>
<P>
"We are not going to water down our ideas," she told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Seeking to couch the U.S. demands in reasonable terms, Albright
said the 13 percent pullback proposal was much closer to Israel's
position than to the Palestinians' and did not attempt to define
what territory Israel should give up. That, she said, was up to
Israel.
</P>
<P>
Albright denied that the United States was giving ultimatums or
threatening Israel's security. The U.S. proposals were just
"suggestions," she said.
</P>
<P>
State Department spokesman James Rubin said Albright's speech
sought to show how far U.S. ideas met criteria laid down by Israel
itself. They came closer to Israel's offer -- of a 9 percent
withdrawal -- than to Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat's original
demand of 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
After the speech, Albright went to the Capitol Hill to try to
win support among members of Congress for the administration's
stand. House Speaker Newt Gingrich and several other leading
Republicans have accused the Clinton administration of unfairly
pressuring Israel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
